{"title_page": "Le\u00f3n Err\u00e1zuriz", "text_new": "'''Le\u00f3n Err\u00e1zuriz''' (born 23 July in [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], [[Chile]]) is a filmmaker now based in Los Angeles, USA.\n\nHe is earned a degree in Economics at the [[Catholic University of Chile]] 1991, and also studied for a few years at the [[Centro Universitario de Estudios Cinematogr\u00e1ficos]] of the [[UNAM]] Mexican film school. Back in Chile he directed many commercials spots and his first feature film ''Mala Leche'' in late 2004, winning the Horizons Award at the 52 [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]].\n\n== Awards ==\n* [[Altazor Awards]]: ''Best Director Drama Television'' with ''[[Huaquim\u00e1n y Tolosa]]'' - 2007\n* [[New York LaCinemaFe]]: ''Honorable Mention'' with ''[[Mala leche]]'' - (35mm,100 minutes) - 2005\n* [[Gramado Film Festival]]: ''Nominated'' with ''[[Mala leche]]'' - (35mm,100 minutes) -2005\n* [[Festival Cinesul Brasil]]: ''Won'' with ''[[Mala leche]]'' - (35mm,100 minutes) -2005\n* [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]]: ''Won Horizons Awards with [[Mala leche]]''(35mm,100 minutes)- 2004\n* 1999\u20132003 in two occasions he obtained awards from ACHAP (Chilean National Association of Advertising)\n\n== Filmography as director ==\n* 2010 - ''Letter of Consuelo'' / a historical TV film about Land Reform in Chile (1971\u20131973) ([[Chilevision]])\n* 2010 - ''Free Falling Atacama'' / Feature Film (Director, Script, Edition)[http://vimeo.com/12452159]\n* 2009 - ''The Goatherd'' / Feature Film (Director, Script, Edition)[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1548553/]\n* 2007 - ''[[Cam\u00e9ra Caf\u00e9]]'' / Director Pilot Chile / Serie TV ([[Cuatro Cabezas|4K]])\n* 2007 - ''Che Kopete la pel\u00edcula''/ Feature Film (Director).[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a3CsHsW0tnI]\n* 2006 - ''[[Huaiquim\u00e1n y Tolosa]]'' [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0848615/] private detectives (Police comedy) / Serie TV ([[Canal 13 (Chile)|canal 13]]) (director, original idea) [[:es:Huaiquim\u00e1n y Tolosa]][https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0N8pYnv4wzg]\n* 2004 - ''Mala leche'' / Feature Film [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0410288/](Director, script, executive production, Edition)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9rxL6lmOzCQ]\n\nwith his production company Cine FX he Co-produce Para\u00edso B (2002), [[Sexo con amor]] (2003), Jemeaux (2003) y Huaiquim\u00e1n y Tolosa Investigadores privados / Serie TV(2006).\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1636674}}\n* [http://vimeo.com/user1889611/videos Vimeo]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/leonerrazuriz Le\u00f3n Err\u00e1zuriz en Youtube]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100514021340/http://leonerrazuriz.com/ Le\u00f3n Err\u00e1zuriz Mala Leche]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110831124517/http://www.premioaltazor.cl/leon-errazuriz-huaiquiman-y-tolosa/ Altazor]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071026092923/http://sansebastian.mister-i.com/peli.jsp?id=520620 San Sebastian]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101107051106/http://www.jaman.com/movie/Mala-Leche/0-zly-8Kudx0/ Jaman]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n                   <!-- Goes above DEFAULTSORT/Categories -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Errazuriz, Leon}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chilean film directors]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Catholic University of Chile alumni]]\n\n\n{{Chile-film-director-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Le\u00f3n Err\u00e1zuriz''' (born 23 July in [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], [[Chile]]) is a filmmaker now based in Los Angeles, USA.\n\nHe is earned a degree in Economics at the [[Catholic University of Chile]] 1991, and also studied for a few years at the [[Centro Universitario de Estudios Cinematogr\u00e1ficos]] of the [[UNAM]] Mexican film school. Back in Chile he directed many commercials spots and his first feature film ''Mala Leche'' in late 2004, winning the Horizons Award at the 52 [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]].\n\n== Awards ==\n* [[Altazor Awards]]: ''Best Director Drama Television'' with ''[[Huaquim\u00e1n y Tolosa]]'' - 2007\n* [[New York LaCinemaFe]]: ''Honorable Mention'' with ''[[Mala leche]]'' - (35mm,100 minutes) - 2005\n* [[Gramado Film Festival]]: ''Nominated'' with ''[[Mala leche]]'' - (35mm,100 minutes) -2005\n* [[Festival Cinesul Brasil]]: ''Won'' with ''[[Mala leche]]'' - (35mm,100 minutes) -2005\n* [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]]: ''Won Horizons Awards with [[Mala leche]]''(35mm,100 minutes)- 2004\n* 1999-2003 in two occasions he obtained awards from ACHAP (Chilean National Association of Advertising)\n\n== Filmography as director ==\n* 2010 - ''Letter of Consuelo'' / a historical TV film about Land Reform in Chile (1971\u20131973) ([[Chilevision]])\n* 2010 - ''Free Falling Atacama'' / Feature Film (Director, Script, Edition)[http://vimeo.com/12452159]\n* 2009 - ''The Goatherd'' / Feature Film (Director, Script, Edition)[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1548553/]\n* 2007 - ''[[Cam\u00e9ra Caf\u00e9]]'' / Director Pilot Chile / Serie TV ([[Cuatro Cabezas|4K]])\n* 2007 - ''Che Kopete la pel\u00edcula''/ Feature Film (Director).[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a3CsHsW0tnI]\n* 2006 - ''[[Huaiquim\u00e1n y Tolosa]]'' [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0848615/] private detectives (Police comedy) / Serie TV ([[Canal 13 (Chile)|canal 13]]) (director, original idea) [[:es:Huaiquim\u00e1n y Tolosa]][https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0N8pYnv4wzg]\n* 2004 - ''Mala leche'' / Feature Film [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0410288/](Director, script, executive production, Edition)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9rxL6lmOzCQ]\n\nwith his production company Cine FX he Co-produce Para\u00edso B (2002), [[Sexo con amor]] (2003), Jemeaux (2003) y Huaiquim\u00e1n y Tolosa Investigadores privados / Serie TV(2006).\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1636674}}\n* [http://vimeo.com/user1889611/videos Vimeo]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/leonerrazuriz Le\u00f3n Err\u00e1zuriz en Youtube]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100514021340/http://leonerrazuriz.com/ Le\u00f3n Err\u00e1zuriz Mala Leche]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110831124517/http://www.premioaltazor.cl/leon-errazuriz-huaiquiman-y-tolosa/ Altazor]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071026092923/http://sansebastian.mister-i.com/peli.jsp?id=520620 San Sebastian]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101107051106/http://www.jaman.com/movie/Mala-Leche/0-zly-8Kudx0/ Jaman]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n                   <!-- Goes above DEFAULTSORT/Categories -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Errazuriz, Leon}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chilean film directors]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Catholic University of Chile alumni]]\n\n\n{{Chile-film-director-stub}}\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1999-2003 \u2192 1999\u20132003", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le%C3%B3n_Err%C3%A1zuriz"}
{"title_page": "Levi L. Rowland", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Levi L. Rowland\n| image         = Levi L. Rowland.jpeg\n| imagesize     = 120px\n| caption       = \n| office        = [[Oregon Superintendent of Public Instruction]]\n| term          = September 14, 1874 &ndash; September 9, 1878\n| governor      = [[La Fayette Grover]]<br>[[Stephen F. Chadwick]]\n| constituency  = \n| nominator     = \n| appointer     = \n| predecessor   = [[Sylvester C. Simpson]]\n| successor     = [[Leonard J. Powell]]\n| office2       = [[Oregon State Hospital|Superintendent of the Oregon Insane Asylum]]\n| termstart2    = July 8, 1891\n| termend2      = August 1, 1895\n| nominator2    = \n| appointer2    = \n| predecessor2  = [[Harry Lane]]\n| successor2    = D. A. Paine\n| birth_date    = September 17, 1831\n| birth_place   = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1908|1|19|1831|9|17}}\n| death_place   = [[Salem, Oregon]]\n| party         = Republican\n| spouse        = Emma J. Sanders\n}}\nDr '''Levi Lindsey Rowland''' [[FRSE]] (September 17, 1831 &ndash; January 19, 1908) was an [[United States|American]] educator and physician in the state of [[Oregon]]. A native of [[Tennessee]], he served as the [[Oregon Superintendent of Public Instruction]], president of what became [[Western Oregon University]], and as the Superintendent of Oregon's insane asylum, now the [[Oregon State Hospital]]. The Republican was also a pastor and farmer.\n\n==Early years==\nLevi Rowland was born in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], on September 17, 1831, the son of Jeremiah and Lucy (''n\u00e9e'' Butler) Rowland.<ref name=Oregon>Corning, Howard M. (1989) ''Dictionary of Oregon History''. [[Binfords & Mort Publishing]]. p. 212.</ref> In 1844, he came over the [[Oregon Trail]] with his parents and settled in the [[Yamhill County, Oregon|Yamhill District]] in the [[Oregon Country]].<ref name=\"dead\">{{cite news|title=Dr. L. L. Rowland Dead|date=January 20, 1908|work=[[The Oregonian|Oregonian]]|page=2}}</ref> After farming for a few years he left what was then the [[Oregon Territory]] in 1849 and headed south to the gold mines of California during the [[California Gold Rush]].<ref name=Oregon/> Rowland returned to Oregon in 1851 after accumulating some wealth, but then returned east to [[Virginia]] to attend college.<ref name=Oregon/> In 1856, he graduated from [[Bethany College (West Virginia)|Bethany College]] in Virginia (now [[West Virginia]]) and was ordained as a minister of the [[Disciples of Christ]].<ref name=\"wv\">{{cite book|last=Lang|first=H. O.|title=History of the Willamette Valley Being a Description of the Valley and Its Resources, with an Account of Its Discovery and Settlement by White Men, and Its Subsequent History, Together with Personal Reminiscences of Its Early Pioneers|publisher=Himes & Lang.|location=Portland, Oregon|year=1885|pages= [https://archive.org/details/histwillvalley00langrich/page/628 628]\u2013629|oclc=16739827|url=https://archive.org/details/histwillvalley00langrich}}</ref>\n\n==Educator and doctor==\nAfter graduation from college, Rowland spent time in the eastern United States as a teacher and as a minister.<ref name=Oregon/> He married Emma J. Sanders in 1859, and they had five children.<ref name=\"wv\"/> That year he returned to what had become the state of Oregon and served as the principal at the [[Bethel, Polk County, Oregon|Bethel Institute]] in the [[Eola Hills]] in [[Polk County, Oregon|Polk County]].<ref name=\"dead\"/><ref name=\"ode\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ode.state.or.us/search/page/?id=632|title=Superintendent Tenures|publisher=[[Oregon Department of Education]]|accessdate=21 February 2010}}</ref> Rowland worked as the principal until 1861, but in 1860 he became the superintendent of Polk County's schools.<ref name=Oregon/> In 1862, he started the first teacher's institute in Oregon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wou.edu/provost/library/archives/university/presidents/Rowland.php|title=Levi L. Rowland|work=Hamersly Library: Presidential Biographies|publisher=Western Oregon University|accessdate=21 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe then served as the president of Monmouth Christian College (now [[Western Oregon University]]) in [[Monmouth, Oregon|Monmouth]] in Polk County from 1866 to 1869.<ref name=\"dead\"/> His former school, Bethel Institute, had merged with the later school in 1865,<ref>Corning, p. 28.</ref> and he became the first president of the school.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Almack|first=John C. |date=March 1920|title=Oregon Normal Schools|journal=Oregon Historical Quarterly|publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]]|volume=21|issue=1|pages=106|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6lRTvbfnwVgC&dq=%22Sylvester%20Simpson%22&as_brr=1&pg=RA1-PA106&ci=207%2C236%2C691%2C391&source=bookclip}}</ref> Rowland left the college in order to start [[medical school]] at [[Willamette University College of Medicine]] in Salem, and where he graduated in 1872.<ref name=Oregon/> While still in school he served as a professor at the medical school from 1870 until 1878.<ref name=Oregon/>\n\nRowland was elected as [[Oregon Superintendent of Public Instruction]] in 1874, while still working as a professor at Willamette.<ref name=Oregon/> He was the first person elected to that office, as his predecessor had been appointed when the office was still part of the [[Governor of Oregon|governor's office]].<ref name=\"sos\">{{cite journal|last=Kincaid|first=Harrison Rittenhouse|year=1899|title=Superintendents of Public Instruction|journal=Political and Official History and Register of Oregon|publisher=State of Oregon|pages=10, 16, 217\u2013218|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AZQtAAAAYAAJ&q=rowland#v=snippet&q=rowland&f=false}}</ref> He served as state superintendent until 1878 when he then traveled around Europe and Asia.<ref name=\"dead\"/> Also during his time in Salem he was the pastor of the First Christian Church.<ref name=Oregon/> After returning to Oregon from his trip abroad he worked on his farm and started an insurance company, as well as serving as president the State Insurance Society.<ref name=Oregon/><ref name=\"wv\"/>\n\n==Later years==\nIn 1891, he returned to public office when he was elected as the Superintendent of the Insane Asylum, now known as the [[Oregon State Hospital]].<ref name=\"dead\"/> A Republican, he served in that office until 1895 when he retired to his country estate at [[Mehama, Oregon|Mehama]] in [[Marion County, Oregon|Marion County]].<ref name=\"sos\"/><ref name=\"untitled\">{{cite news|title=Untitled (Column 4)|date=January 21, 1908|work=[[The Oregonian|Oregonian]]|page=6}}</ref> He later began to suffer from several illnesses and moved to his home in Salem.<ref name=\"dead\"/> Levi Lindsey Rowland died on January 19, 1908, in Salem at the age of 76 of [[dropsy]].<ref name=\"dead\"/><ref name=\"untitled\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=6j8QAAAAYAAJ&vq=rowland&pg=RA4-PA363&ci=155%2C657%2C253%2C25&source=bookclip Republican League Register]\n*[http://ncbible.org/nwh/ProRowland.html Pioneer Preacher Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef | before=position created}}\n{{s-ttl | title=President of [[Western Oregon University|Monmouth Christian College]] | years = 1866&ndash;1869}}\n{{s-aft | after=Thomas Franklin Campbell }}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rowland, Levi L.}}\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Yamhill County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:1831 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:Oregon Superintendents of Public Instruction]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Salem, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Willamette University faculty]]\n[[Category:Heads of universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Willamette University alumni]]\n[[Category:Western Oregon University faculty]]\n[[Category:Bethany College (West Virginia) alumni]]\n[[Category:Oregon Republicans]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Willamette University College of Medicine alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Politician\n| name          = Levi L. Rowland\n| image         = Levi L. Rowland.jpeg\n| imagesize     = 120px\n| caption       = \n| office        = [[Oregon Superintendent of Public Instruction]]\n| term          = September 14, 1874 &ndash; September 9, 1878\n| governor      = [[La Fayette Grover]]<br>[[Stephen F. Chadwick]]\n| constituency  = \n| nominator     = \n| appointer     = \n| predecessor   = [[Sylvester C. Simpson]]\n| successor     = [[Leonard J. Powell]]\n| office2       = [[Oregon State Hospital|Superintendent of the Oregon Insane Asylum]]\n| termstart2    = July 8, 1891\n| termend2      = August 1, 1895\n| nominator2    = \n| appointer2    = \n| predecessor2  = [[Harry Lane]]\n| successor2    = D. A. Paine\n| birth_date    = September 17, 1831\n| birth_place   = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1908|1|19|1831|9|17}}\n| death_place   = [[Salem, Oregon]]\n| party         = Republican\n| spouse        = Emma J. Sanders\n}}\nDr '''Levi Lindsey Rowland''' [[FRSE]] (September 17, 1831 &ndash; January 19, 1908) was an [[United States|American]] educator and physician in the state of [[Oregon]]. A native of [[Tennessee]], he served as the [[Oregon Superintendent of Public Instruction]], president of what became [[Western Oregon University]], and as the Superintendent of Oregon\u2019s insane asylum, now the [[Oregon State Hospital]]. The Republican was also a pastor and farmer.\n\n==Early years==\nLevi Rowland was born in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], on September 17, 1831, the son of Jeremiah and Lucy (''n\u00e9e'' Butler) Rowland.<ref name=Oregon>Corning, Howard M. (1989) ''Dictionary of Oregon History''. [[Binfords & Mort Publishing]]. p. 212.</ref> In 1844, he came over the [[Oregon Trail]] with his parents and settled in the [[Yamhill County, Oregon|Yamhill District]] in the [[Oregon Country]].<ref name=\"dead\">{{cite news|title=Dr. L. L. Rowland Dead|date=January 20, 1908|work=[[The Oregonian|Oregonian]]|page=2}}</ref> After farming for a few years he left what was then the [[Oregon Territory]] in 1849 and headed south to the gold mines of California during the [[California Gold Rush]].<ref name=Oregon/> Rowland returned to Oregon in 1851 after accumulating some wealth, but then returned east to [[Virginia]] to attend college.<ref name=Oregon/> In 1856, he graduated from [[Bethany College (West Virginia)|Bethany College]] in Virginia (now [[West Virginia]]) and was ordained as a minister of the [[Disciples of Christ]].<ref name=\"wv\">{{cite book|last=Lang|first=H. O.|title=History of the Willamette Valley Being a Description of the Valley and Its Resources, with an Account of Its Discovery and Settlement by White Men, and Its Subsequent History, Together with Personal Reminiscences of Its Early Pioneers|publisher=Himes & Lang.|location=Portland, Oregon|year=1885|pages= [https://archive.org/details/histwillvalley00langrich/page/628 628]\u2013629|oclc=16739827|url=https://archive.org/details/histwillvalley00langrich}}</ref>\n\n==Educator and doctor==\nAfter graduation from college, Rowland spent time in the eastern United States as a teacher and as a minister.<ref name=Oregon/> He married Emma J. Sanders in 1859, and they had five children.<ref name=\"wv\"/> That year he returned to what had become the state of Oregon and served as the principal at the [[Bethel, Polk County, Oregon|Bethel Institute]] in the [[Eola Hills]] in [[Polk County, Oregon|Polk County]].<ref name=\"dead\"/><ref name=\"ode\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ode.state.or.us/search/page/?id=632|title=Superintendent Tenures|publisher=[[Oregon Department of Education]]|accessdate=21 February 2010}}</ref> Rowland worked as the principal until 1861, but in 1860 he became the superintendent of Polk County\u2019s schools.<ref name=Oregon/> In 1862, he started the first teacher\u2019s institute in Oregon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wou.edu/provost/library/archives/university/presidents/Rowland.php|title=Levi L. Rowland|work=Hamersly Library: Presidential Biographies|publisher=Western Oregon University|accessdate=21 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe then served as the president of Monmouth Christian College (now [[Western Oregon University]]) in [[Monmouth, Oregon|Monmouth]] in Polk County from 1866 to 1869.<ref name=\"dead\"/> His former school, Bethel Institute, had merged with the later school in 1865,<ref>Corning, p. 28.</ref> and he became the first president of the school.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Almack|first=John C. |date=March 1920|title=Oregon Normal Schools|journal=Oregon Historical Quarterly|publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]]|volume=21|issue=1|pages=106|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6lRTvbfnwVgC&dq=%22Sylvester%20Simpson%22&as_brr=1&pg=RA1-PA106&ci=207%2C236%2C691%2C391&source=bookclip}}</ref> Rowland left the college in order to start [[medical school]] at [[Willamette University College of Medicine]] in Salem, and where he graduated in 1872.<ref name=Oregon/> While still in school he served as a professor at the medical school from 1870 until 1878.<ref name=Oregon/>\n\nRowland was elected as [[Oregon Superintendent of Public Instruction]] in 1874, while still working as a professor at Willamette.<ref name=Oregon/> He was the first person elected to that office, as his predecessor had been appointed when the office was still part of the [[Governor of Oregon|governor\u2019s office]].<ref name=\"sos\">{{cite journal|last=Kincaid|first=Harrison Rittenhouse|year=1899|title=Superintendents of Public Instruction|journal=Political and Official History and Register of Oregon|publisher=State of Oregon|pages=10, 16, 217\u2013218|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AZQtAAAAYAAJ&q=rowland#v=snippet&q=rowland&f=false}}</ref> He served as state superintendent until 1878 when he then traveled around Europe and Asia.<ref name=\"dead\"/> Also during his time in Salem he was the pastor of the First Christian Church.<ref name=Oregon/> After returning to Oregon from his trip abroad he worked on his farm and started an insurance company, as well as serving as president the State Insurance Society.<ref name=Oregon/><ref name=\"wv\"/>\n\n==Later years==\nIn 1891, he returned to public office when he was elected as the Superintendent of the Insane Asylum, now known as the [[Oregon State Hospital]].<ref name=\"dead\"/> A Republican, he served in that office until 1895 when he retired to his country estate at [[Mehama, Oregon|Mehama]] in [[Marion County, Oregon|Marion County]].<ref name=\"sos\"/><ref name=\"untitled\">{{cite news|title=Untitled (Column 4)|date=January 21, 1908|work=[[The Oregonian|Oregonian]]|page=6}}</ref> He later began to suffer from several illnesses and moved to his home in Salem.<ref name=\"dead\"/> Levi Lindsey Rowland died on January 19, 1908, in Salem at the age of 76 of [[dropsy]].<ref name=\"dead\"/><ref name=\"untitled\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=6j8QAAAAYAAJ&vq=rowland&pg=RA4-PA363&ci=155%2C657%2C253%2C25&source=bookclip Republican League Register]\n*[http://ncbible.org/nwh/ProRowland.html Pioneer Preacher Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef | before=position created}}\n{{s-ttl | title=President of [[Western Oregon University|Monmouth Christian College]] | years = 1866&ndash;1869}}\n{{s-aft | after=Thomas Franklin Campbell }}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rowland, Levi L.}}\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Yamhill County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:1831 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:Oregon Superintendents of Public Instruction]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Salem, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Willamette University faculty]]\n[[Category:Heads of universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Willamette University alumni]]\n[[Category:Western Oregon University faculty]]\n[[Category:Bethany College (West Virginia) alumni]]\n[[Category:Oregon Republicans]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Willamette University College of Medicine alumni]]\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levi_L._Rowland"}
{"title_page": "Andy Garc\u00eda", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor and director}}\n{{Spanish name|[[Garc\u00eda (surname)|Garc\u00eda]]|[[Men\u00e9ndez (disambiguation)|Men\u00e9ndez]]}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}} \n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Andy Garc\u00eda\n| image        = Andy Garcia at the 2009 Deauville American Film Festival-01A.jpg\n| caption      = Garc\u00eda at the 2009 [[Deauville American Film Festival]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1956|4|12}}\n| birth_place  = [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]\n| residence   = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| birth_name   = Andr\u00e9s Arturo Garc\u00eda Men\u00e9ndez\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Marivi Lorido Garc\u00eda|1982}}\n| children     = 4, including [[Dominik Garc\u00eda-Lorido]]\n| height   =\n| occupation   = [[Actor]], [[Film director|director]]\n| years_active = 1978\u2013present\n}}\n'''Andr\u00e9s Arturo Garc\u00eda Men\u00e9ndez''' (born April 12, 1956) is an American actor and director. He is known for his appearances in successful 1980s and 1990s [[Hollywood]] films, including ''[[The Godfather Part III]]'', ''[[The Untouchables (film)|The Untouchables]]'', ''[[Internal Affairs (film)|Internal Affairs]]'' and ''[[When a Man Loves a Woman (film)|When a Man Loves a Woman]]''. In the 2000s, he was rude to comedian John Mulaney at a Lakers game and starred in ''[[Ocean's Eleven]]'' and its [[sequel]]s, ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' and ''[[Ocean's Thirteen]]'', and in ''[[The Lost City (2005 film)|The Lost City]]''. In recent years he's had a career resurgence in such films as ''[[Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again]]'', ''[[Book Club (film)|Book Club]]'', ''[[The Mule (2018 film)|The Mule]]'' and ''[[My Dinner with Herv\u00e9]]''.\n\nGarc\u00eda was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his role as [[Vincent Corleone|Vincent Mancini]] in ''The Godfather Part III''. He was [[Emmy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award]] nominated for his titular role in ''[[For Love or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nGarcia was born Andr\u00e9s Arturo Garc\u00eda Men\u00e9ndez in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]. His mother, Amelie Men\u00e9ndez, was an  English teacher and his father, Ren\u00e9 Garc\u00eda N\u00fa\u00f1ez, was an [[avocado]] farmer and attorney in Cuba who later owned a fragrance business in the United States.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/07/24/movies/new-face-a-fervor-for-film-pays-off-andy-garcia.html | work=The New York Times | title=New Face; A Fervor For Film Pays Off: Andy Garcia | first=Eleanor | last=Blau | date=July 24, 1987 | accessdate=April 25, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/46/Andy-Garcia.html |title=Andy Garcia Biography (2010\u2013) |website=Filmreference.com |date=April 12, 1956 |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref> Garc\u00eda has two older siblings, a sister named Tessi and a brother named Ren\u00e9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tessigarcia.com/Publications/pub-august01.htm |title=Archived copy |website=tessigarcia.com|accessdate=2015-03-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402151029/http://www.tessigarcia.com/Publications/pub-august01.htm |archivedate=April 2, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> When Garc\u00eda was five years old, his family moved to [[Miami]], [[Florida]], after the failed [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]]. Over a period of several years, they built up a million-dollar perfume company. Garc\u00eda was raised as a Roman Catholic<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news| author=Drake, Tim|url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/actor-andy-garcia-fights-for-religious-freedom-in-for-greater-glory |title=Actor Andy Garcia Fights for Religious Freedom in 'For Greater Glory'|work=[[National Catholic Register]]|date= 13 April 2012|access-date= 2 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/jul/19/andy-garcia-decca-aitkenhead | work=[[guardian.co.uk]] | title=Andy Garcia: 'The problem with producing movies? You get paid last' | first=Decca | last=Aitkenhead | date=July 19, 2010 | accessdate=April 27, 2011}}</ref> and attended [[Miami Beach Senior High School]], where he played on the basketball team. During his last year in high school, he became ill with [[Infectious mononucleosis|Mono]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebiographychannel.co.uk/biography_home/19:0/Andy_Garcia.htm |title=Andy Garcia Biography |website=The Biography Channel |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015080245/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biography_home/19%3A0/Andy_Garcia.htm |archivedate=October 15, 2009 }}</ref> which convinced him to pursue a career in acting. He began his acting career by taking a drama class with [[Jay W. Jensen]] in his senior year. He graduated from [[Florida International University]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.netglimse.com/celebs/pages/andy_garcia/index.shtml | title=Andy Garcia \u2013 Biography | accessdate=December 19, 2010 | publisher=Net Glimpse}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP sources section|date=October 2018}}\n[[File:Andy Garcia at Incirlik.jpg|thumb|left|At the flight line tower, [[\u0130ncirlik Air Base]], Turkey, December 7, 2001]]\nGarc\u00eda began acting at Florida International University but soon went to Hollywood. He had a short role in the first episode of ''Murder, She Wrote'' as \"1st white tough\", in 1984. He played the role of a gang member in the first episode of TV series ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''. He appeared in a supporting role in ''[[The Mean Season]]'' in 1985, alongside [[Kurt Russell]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1985-02-14-ca-2668-story.html|title=MOVIE REVIEW : 'THE MEAN SEASON' GETS DOWN TO HUMAN NATURE|date=1985-02-14|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> and director [[Brian De Palma]] cast him in ''[[The Untouchables (film)|The Untouchables]]'' in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/andy-garcia-a-gunslinger-on-the-right-side-of-the-untouchables-who-turns-out-to-be-a-hit-man-vol-28-no-5/|title=Andy Garcia, a Gunslinger on the Right Side of The Untouchables, Who Turns Out to Be a Hit, Man|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda acted in the Ridley Scott film ''[[Black Rain (1989 American film)|Black Rain]]'' in 1989 with Michael Douglas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/blackrainrkempley_a09fde.htm|title=Black Rain|website=www.washingtonpost.com|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> [[Francis Ford Coppola]] cast Garcia as [[Vincent Corleone|Vincent Mancini]], the illegitimate son of [[Sonny Corleone]], in ''[[The Godfather Part III]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1990-12-25-9003040280-story.html|title=CHARACTERS POWER STRONG STORY OF 'GODFATHER III'|last=Writer|first=CANDICE RUSSELL, Film|website=Sun-Sentinel.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> Garc\u00eda earned an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination as [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for his performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1994-05-27-1994147179-story.html|title=Andy Garcia is equal parts leading man and family Man|last=Wuntch|first=Philip|website=baltimoresun.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, Garc\u00eda appeared in ''[[Internal Affairs (film)|Internal Affairs]]'', in which he engages in a battle of wits with a corrupt fellow police officer, played by [[Richard Gere]]. He played a [[Cynicism (contemporary)|cynical]] [[everyman]] in ''[[Hero (1992 film)|Hero]]'', the enabling husband of an alcoholic in ''[[When a Man Loves a Woman (film)|When a Man Loves a Woman]]'', a tragic criminal in ''[[Things to Do in Denver When You're Dead]]'', a hotshot lawyer in the drama ''[[Night Falls on Manhattan]]'' and a cop trying to save his gravely ill son in the action thriller ''[[Desperate Measures (film)|Desperate Measures]]''. He played mobster Lucky Luciano in ''[[Hoodlum (film)|Hoodlum]]''.\n\nHe portrayed the arrogant Las Vegas casino owner Terry Benedict in ''[[Ocean's Eleven (2001 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'', a remake of the 1960 [[Rat Pack]] caper movie. He also appeared in the sequel, ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' and in the third film, ''[[Ocean's Thirteen]]''.\n\nHe co-wrote, directed, and starred in ''[[The Lost City (2005 film)|The Lost City]]'' alongside [[Dustin Hoffman]] and [[Bill Murray]].<ref>{{Citation|title=The Lost City (2005)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0343996/fullcredits/|accessdate=2018-05-31}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he appeared in the last episode of the Turkish TV series ''[[Kurtlar Vadisi]]'', along with [[Sharon Stone]].\n\n===Career resurgence===\nGarcia has had a recent career resurgence in film. He starred in four films in 2018. He starred in the critical and box office success ''[[Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again]]'' as Fernando Cienfuegos alongside ''[[Cher]]'', [[Amanda Seyfried]], [[Lily James]], [[Colin Firth]], [[Stellan Skarsgaard]] and [[Pierce Brosnan]]. The film is Certified Fresh on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] with an 81%, with the critics consensus reading, \"''Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again'' doubles down on just about everything fans loved about the original -- and my my, how can fans resist it?\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again (2018)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mamma_mia_here_we_go_again|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> When asked about singing with [[Cher]], Garcia told NBC\u2019s ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' show, \u201cIt was sublime. One thing is to act with Cher who is a great actress and then to be asked to sing with her\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/features/fl-reg-mamma-mia-sequel-andy-garcia-plays-fernando-20180718-story.html|title=Miami's Andy Garcia talks about playing 'Fernando' and singing with Cher in 'Mamma Mia' sequel|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|website=sun-sentinel.com|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nGarcia also starred in the [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] romantic comedy, ''[[Book Club (film)|Book Club]]'', alongside [[Diane Keaton]], [[Candice Bergen]], [[Jane Fonda]] and [[Mary Steenburgen]]. The film was a box office success grossing over $89 million worldwide against its $10 million budget.\n\nHe also starred in [[Clint Eastwood]]'s drama film, ''[[The Mule (2018 film)|The Mule]]'' alongside Eastwood, [[Bradley Cooper]], [[Dianne Wiest]], [[Laurence Fishburne]] and [[Michael Pena]]. It has grossed $166 million and received positive reviews from critics, who called it \"poignant and charming\" and praised Eastwood's performance.\n\nHe also appeared in the acclaimed [[HBO]] movie ''[[My Dinner with Herv\u00e9]]'' alongside [[Peter Dinklage]] and [[Jamie Dornan]]. Rotten Tomatoes gives the film an approval rating of 83% with the site's critical consensus reading, \"''My Dinner with Herv\u00e9'' offers a standard narrative on celebrity and infamy but formidable performances by Peter Dinklage and Jamie Dornan find the dimensionality and pathos of Herv\u00e9 Villechaize the man.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=My Dinner with Herv\u00e9 (2018)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/my_dinner_with_herve|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> The film received a [[Critics Choice Television Awards|Critics Choice Television Award]] nomination for [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Movie/Miniseries|Best Movie/Miniseries]].\n\n===Hemingway project===\n[[File:Julianna Margulies Andy Garcia and Dominik Garcia at the Tribeca Film Festival.jpg|thumb|At the 2009 [[Tribeca Film Festival]] with [[Julianna Margulies]] (left) and his daughter [[Dominik Garc\u00eda-Lorido]]]]\nGarc\u00eda has been slated to direct the upcoming film ''Hemingway & Fuentes'' about famous writer [[Ernest Hemingway]] co-written by Garc\u00eda and Hemingway's niece [[Hilary Hemingway]]. Originally, announced stars included [[Anthony Hopkins]], [[Annette Bening]] and Garc\u00eda himself. Filming was originally to have begun in January 2013,<ref name=Collider2>{{cite web|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|title=HEMINGWAY & FUENTES Finally Moving Forward with Anthony Hopkins, Annette Bening, and Andy Garcia |url=http://collider.com/hemingway-fuentes-andy-garcia-anthony-hopkins/ |publisher=Collider|accessdate=March 24, 2014|date=May 16, 2012}}</ref><ref name=HollywoodReporter>{{cite web |last=Kit |first=Borys |title=Cannes 2012: Anthony Hopkins and Andy Garcia to Film 'Hemingway & Fuentes'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-2012-anthony-hopkins-andy-garcia-anthony-hemingway-fuentes-324704|publisher=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=March 24, 2014|date=May 16, 2012}}</ref> but due to delays, Hopkins left the project and Garcia announced that the role of Hemingway would be played by actor [[Jon Voight]].<ref>{{cite news|last=staff|title=Sir Anthony Hopkins exits Andy Garcia's Ernest Hemingway movie|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/showbiz/456848/Sir-Anthony-Hopkins-exits-Andy-Garcia-s-Ernest-Hemingway-movie|accessdate=March 31, 2014|newspaper=[[Daily Express|Express]]|date=January 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Molina|first=Melissa|title=Interview: Andy Garcia Talks About 'At Middleton,' 'Hemingway & Fuentes'|url=http://screencrave.com/2014-02-04/interview-andy-garcia-talks-at-middleton-hemingway-fuentes/|accessdate=March 31, 2014|newspaper=Screen Crave|date=February 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227123916/http://screencrave.com/2014-02-04/interview-andy-garcia-talks-at-middleton-hemingway-fuentes/|archive-date=February 27, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1982, Garc\u00eda married Marivi Lorido.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/02/25/earlyshow/leisure/celebspot/main602254.shtml | work=CBS News | title=Andy Garcia's 'Twisted' Role | date=February 25, 2004}}</ref> The couple has four children: daughters [[Dominik Garc\u00eda-Lorido]] (b. 1983), Daniella (b. 1988), Alessandra (b. 1991) and son Andres (b. 2002).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-6345711_ITM |work=[[Knight Ridder/Tribune News Service]] |title='Steal Big' star Andy Garcia was ready for a more light-hearted role.(Originated from ''The Virginian-Pilot'') |date=September 29, 1995 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314232640/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-6345711_ITM |archivedate=March 14, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SJ&s_site=mercurynews&p_multi=SJ&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F16454B728ADC9B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D |title=Andy Garcia, Family Welcome Arrival of New Son |work=San Jose Mercury News |date=January 30, 2002 |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref> The family divide their time between [[Toluca Lake, Los Angeles]] and [[Key Biscayne, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/12/movies/his-homeland-his-obsession.html |title = His Homeland, His Obsession|newspaper = The New York Times|date = February 12, 2005|last1 = Ojito|first1 = Mirta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/andy-garcias-house-2/view/google/ |title = Andy Garcia's House in Key Biscayne, FL (Google Maps) (#3)|date = September 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda has expressed, on a number of occasions, his distaste to the [[Communism|communist]] regime that has ruled [[Cuba]] since the [[Cuban Revolution|revolution]] that occurred there from 1953 to 1959.<ref name=\"belfasttelegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|url= https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/andy-garcia-condemns-late-fidel-castros-totalitarian-regime-35248581.html | title=Andy Garcia condemns late Fidel Castro's 'totalitarian' regime| work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]| date= 27 November 2016|accessdate= 2 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author=Ojito, Mirta| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/12/movies/his-homeland-his-obsession.html |title= His Homeland, His Obsession |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=12 February 2005|accessdate= 2 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Strauss, Bob|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2014/01/28/andy-garcia-lightens-up-in-rom-com-at-middleton/ |title=Andy Garcia lightens up in rom-com 'At Middleton'|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|date= 28 January 2014|accessdate= 2 August 2018}}</ref> Following [[Fidel Castro|Fidel Castro's]] death in November 2016, Garc\u00eda criticized his legacy, stating: \"It is necessary for me to express the deep sorrow that I feel for all the Cuban people...that have suffered the atrocities and repression caused by Fidel Castro and his totalitarian regime.\"<ref name=\"belfasttelegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nGarc\u00eda is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/actor-andy-garcia-fights-for-religious-freedom-in-for-greater-glory | work=National Catholic Register | title=Actor Andy Garcia Fights for Religious Freedom in 'For Greater Glory' | date= 13 April 2012 |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1983\n| ''[[Blue Skies Again (film)|Blue Skies Again]]''\n| Ken\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Guaguasi]]''\n| Ricardo\n|\n|-\n| ''[[A Night in Heaven]]''\n| T. J. The Bartender\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[The Lonely Guy]]''\n|\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[The Mean Season]]''\n| Ray Mart\u00ednez\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[8 Million Ways to Die]]''\n| Angel Moldonado\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[The Untouchables (film)|The Untouchables]]''\n| Agent George Stone / Giuseppe Petri\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1988\n| ''[[Stand and Deliver]]''\n| Dr. Ram\u00edrez\n|\n|-\n| ''[[American Roulette (film)|American Roulette]]''\n| Carlos Quintas\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| 