{"title_page": "Laxman Kumara", "text_new": "{{about|the character of Mahabharata|other uses|Lakshman (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Laxman Kumara\n| image              = Abhimanyu Kilss Lakshmana.jpg\n| caption            = Abhimanyu kills Lakshmana\n| family             = [[Duryodhana]] (father)<br/>  [[Bhanumati (Mahabharata)|Bhanumati]] (mother)\n}}\nIn the [[Hindu epic]] ''[[Mahabharata]]'', '''Laxman Kumara''' or simply '''Laxman''' ('''Lakshman(a)''') is the son of [[Duryodhana]], and grandson of [[Dhritarashtra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/iml/iml23.htm |title=Indian Myth and Legend: Chapter XVIII. The Battle of Eighteen Days |publisher=Sacred-texts.com |date= }}</ref> He had a twin sister called [[Lakshmanaa]] who was kidnapped by [[Samba (Krishna's son)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krsnabook.com/ch68.html |title=Krishna Book Chapter 68: The Marriage of Samba |publisher=Krsnabook.com |date= }}</ref> Not much is revealed about Laxman in the ''Mahabharata''.\n\n==Vatsala==\n\nThis story is not present in Mahabharata but is actually a [[Telugu people|Telugu]] folklore. Vatsala (Sashirekha), the daughter of [[Balarama]] is betrothed to the [[Pandava]] prince [[Abhimanyu]]. Abhimanyu is the son of Arjuna.\n\nand [[Krishna]]'s sister [[Subhadra]] and (Krishna's close friend) the [[Pandava]] prince [[Arjuna]].\nSo initially the marriage of Vatsala is to be performed with Abhimanyu but when Abhimanyu's father [[Arjuna]] goes into exile Balarama's wife [[Revati]] says that Arjuna has no kingdom left and a prince without a kingdom may well be a commoner. Balarama thinks about it and feels that his wife is right and that he is supposed to think about the welfare of his daughter breaks off the marriage with Abhimanyu.\n\nBalarama arranges it instead with Duryodhana's son Laxman. When Abhimanyu comes to know about and is annoyed. Abhimanyu asks his maternal uncle- Balarama's brother and Arjuna's ally, [[Krishna]] to intervene. Krishna says he cannot do so but he should ask help from his first cousin [[Ghatotkacha]] - the half demon son of Arjuna's brother [[Bheema]] who lives in Varnavat. Abhimanyu sets out to Varnavat and meets his cousin brother and tells him why he seeks his help. Ghatotkacha is furious at Balarama because he wants to keep an alliance with the very people who were the cause of the Pandavas' misery. Meanwhile, the marriage preparations take place at Balarama's house. Ghatotkacha hatches a plan to get Vatsala and Abhimanyu married.\n\nGhatotkacha goes disguised as Vatsala to the marriage ceremony. He frightens the hell out of Laxman who promptly faints. Laxman vows never to marry. The real Vatsala has been transported by Ghatotkacha to Varnavat where Abhimanyu awaits. The couple's marriage is celebrated. When Duryodhana learns that Abhimanyu has married Vatsala, he is infuriated and thus his anger toward the Pandavas is further fuelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boloji.com/index.cfm?md=Content&sd=Articles&ArticleID=11706 |title=Balarama is Abhimanyu\u2019s Father-In-Law: A Study In Folk Mahabharata by Indrajit Bandyopadhyay |publisher=Boloji.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://devdutt.com/articles/mahabharata/caught-in-a-whirlpool.html |title=Caught in a Whirlpool : Devdutt Pattanaik |publisher=Devdutt.com |date=2009-12-27 |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==Role in Kurukshetra war and Death==\n\nHe slain Kshatradeva, Shikhandi's son on the twelfth day of the war. Laxman is slain on the 13th day of the War by Abhimanyu, who decapitates Laxman using the Nagashirashtra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.urday.in/mchakravyuh.htm |title=MAHABHARATA - Chakravyuh Abhimanyu`s Death |publisher=Urday.in |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611120140/http://www.urday.in/mchakravyuh.htm |archive-date=11 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m07/m07043.htm |title=The Mahabharata, Book 7: Drona Parva: Abhimanyu-badha Parva: Section XLIV |publisher=Sacred-texts.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref> Abhimanyu later gets killed by a joint attack of seven warriors.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Duryodhana]]\n{{Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n[[Category:Characters in the Mahabharata]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{about|the character of Mahabharata|other uses|Lakshman (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Laxman Kumara\n| image              = Abhimanyu Kilss Lakshmana.jpg\n| caption            = Abhimanyu kills Lakshmana\n| family             = [[Duryodhana]] (father)<br/>  [[Bhanumati (Mahabharata)|Bhanumati]] (mother)\n}}\nIn the [[Hindu epic]] ''[[Mahabharata]]'', '''Laxman Kumara''' or simply '''Laxman''' ('''Lakshman(a)''') is the son of [[Duryodhana]], and grandson of [[Dhritarashtra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/iml/iml23.htm |title=Indian Myth and Legend: Chapter XVIII. The Battle of Eighteen Days |publisher=Sacred-texts.com |date= }}</ref> He had a twin sister called [[Lakshmanaa]] who was kidnapped by [[Samba (Krishna's son)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krsnabook.com/ch68.html |title=Krishna Book Chapter 68: The Marriage of Samba |publisher=Krsnabook.com |date= }}</ref> Not much is revealed about Laxman in the ''Mahabharata''.\n\n==Vatsala==\n\nThis story is not present in Mahabharata but is actually a [[Telugu people|Telugu]] folklore. Vatsala (Sashirekha), the daughter of [[Balarama]] is betrothed to the [[Pandava]] prince [[Abhimanyu]]. Abhimanyu is the son of Arjuna.\n\nand [[Krishna]]'s sister [[Subhadra]] and (Krishna's close friend) the [[Pandava]] prince [[Arjuna]].\nSo initially the marriage of Vatsala is to be performed with Abhimanyu but when Abhimanyu's father [[Arjuna]] goes into exile Balarama's wife [[Revati]] says that Arjuna has no kingdom left and a prince without a kingdom may well be a commoner. Balarama thinks about it and feels that his wife is right and that he is supposed to think about the welfare of his daughter breaks off the marriage with Abhimanyu.\n\nBalarama arranges it instead with Duryodhana's son Laxman. When Abhimanyu comes to know about and is annoyed. Abhimanyu asks his maternal uncle- Balarama's brother and Arjuna's ally, [[Krishna]] to intervene. Krishna says he cannot do so but he should ask help from his first cousin [[Ghatotkacha]] - the half demon son of Arjuna's brother [[Bheema]] who lives in Varnavat. Abhimanyu sets out to Varnavat and meets his cousin brother and tells him why he seeks his help. Ghatotkacha is furious at Balarama because he wants to keep an alliance with the very people who were the cause of the Pandavas' misery. Meanwhile, the marriage preparations take place at Balarama\u2019s house. Ghatotkacha hatches a plan to get Vatsala and Abhimanyu married.\n\nGhatotkacha goes disguised as Vatsala to the marriage ceremony. He frightens the hell out of Laxman who promptly faints. Laxman vows never to marry. The real Vatsala has been transported by Ghatotkacha to Varnavat where Abhimanyu awaits. The couple\u2019s marriage is celebrated. When Duryodhana learns that Abhimanyu has married Vatsala, he is infuriated and thus his anger toward the Pandavas is further fuelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boloji.com/index.cfm?md=Content&sd=Articles&ArticleID=11706 |title=Balarama is Abhimanyu\u2019s Father-In-Law: A Study In Folk Mahabharata by Indrajit Bandyopadhyay |publisher=Boloji.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://devdutt.com/articles/mahabharata/caught-in-a-whirlpool.html |title=Caught in a Whirlpool : Devdutt Pattanaik |publisher=Devdutt.com |date=2009-12-27 |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==Role in Kurukshetra war and Death==\n\nHe slain Kshatradeva, Shikhandi's son on the twelfth day of the war. Laxman is slain on the 13th day of the War by Abhimanyu, who decapitates Laxman using the Nagashirashtra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.urday.in/mchakravyuh.htm |title=MAHABHARATA - Chakravyuh Abhimanyu`s Death |publisher=Urday.in |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611120140/http://www.urday.in/mchakravyuh.htm |archive-date=11 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m07/m07043.htm |title=The Mahabharata, Book 7: Drona Parva: Abhimanyu-badha Parva: Section XLIV |publisher=Sacred-texts.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref> Abhimanyu later gets killed by a joint attack of seven warriors.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Duryodhana]]\n{{Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n[[Category:Characters in the Mahabharata]]\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laxman_Kumara"}
{"title_page": "Brain on Fire (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Brain on Fire\n| image          = Brain on Fire.jpg\n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Gerard Barrett (director)|Gerard Barrett]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* A.J. Dix \n* Beth Kono \n* Rob Merilees \n*  Lindsay Macadam \n* [[Charlize Theron]]\n}}\n| writer         = Gerard Barrett\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Brain on Fire]]''|[[Susannah Cahalan]]}}\n| starring       =  {{Plainlist|\n* [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]] \n*  [[Jenny Slate]] \n*  [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]] \n* [[Tyler Perry]]\n*  [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] \n*  [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]]\n}}\n| music          = [[John Paesano]]\n| cinematography = Yaron Orbach\n| editing        = JC Bond\n| studio          =  {{Plainlist|\n*  [[Denver and Delilah Productions]]\n*  Foundation Features\n* [[Broad Green Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| released       = {{film date|2016|9|14|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2018|6|22|United States}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes<ref name=\"Brain on Fire\">{{cite web|url=http://tiff.net/films/brain-on-fire/|title=Brain on Fire|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n*  Canada\n*  Ireland \n* United States\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Brain on Fire''''' is a 2016 [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[drama]] film directed and written by [[Irish people|Irish]] filmmaker [[Gerard Barrett (director)|Gerard Barrett]]. The film is based on [[Susannah Cahalan]]'s memoir ''[[Brain on Fire|Brain on Fire: My Month of Madness]]'' and stars [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]], [[Jenny Slate]], [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]], [[Tyler Perry]], [[Carrie-Anne Moss]], and [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]]. The film follows a ''[[New York Post]]'' writer who begins to suffer a mysterious illness. [[Principal photography]] began on July 13, 2015, in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. After being evaluated extensively by many doctors, she was diagnosed to be psychotic. She would have been committed to psychiatric ward in a hospital and probably died of encephalitis, if it weren't for the efforts and skills of a Syrian-American neurologist( Souhel Najjar). He empathized with her case, was able to diagnose and treat her rare illness. It had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 14, 2016. The film was released on [[Netflix]] on June 22, 2018.\n\n== Plot ==\n21-year-old Susannah Cahalan ([[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]]) is a writer for ''[[The New York Post]]'' who lives with her new boyfriend Stephen ([[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]]). Susannah becomes suddenly ill, initially showing symptoms of a common flu like a cough and fatigue, but later begins presenting strange behaviour while in a trance state, such as hearing people say things they haven't said and hypersensitivity to loud noises.\n\nOver time, her behaviour becomes more and more erratic. Finally, Susannah suffers a seizure and seeks medical treatment. The doctor consulted is adamant it is down to Susannah partying too much, working too hard and not getting enough sleep. She moves in with her mother Rhona ([[Carrie-Anne Moss]]) and, after an emotional outburst, suffers another seizure, and is taken to a clinic where she undergoes an [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]]. Susannah also believes she may have [[bipolar disorder]] due to her severe mood changes.\n\nRhona struggles to care for Susannah, and she later moves in with her father Tom ([[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]]) and his new fianc\u00e9. During dinner one night, she becomes violent towards them while suffering another outburst, and her parents demand she is hospitalized despite the MRI, [[Electroencephalography|EEG]], and all other tests showing normal results. In the hospital, one the doctors informs Susannah's parents she could have [[schizophrenia]], and says that if her behaviour does not improve, she will be transferred to a psychiatric hospital. \n\nSusannah gradually becomes catatonic, and [[Souhel Najjar|Dr. Souhel Najjar]] ([[Navid Negahban]]) is asked to help in investigating her case. He has Susannah draw a clock; she draws it with all of the numbers (1\u201312) on the right side of the face, leading Najjar to believe that the right hemisphere of her brain is swollen and inflamed. Najjar has her undergo a brain biopsy in order to take cells from her brain for diagnosis. Following the biopsy, it is found that Susannah has a rare disease called [[anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis]], a brain inflammation, which Najjar describes as \"brain on fire\". Najjar begins treatment, which leads to a slow but full recovery of her cognitive abilities.\n\nSeven months later, Susannah is back at work. She presents her first written piece since her recovery to her boss Richard ([[Tyler Perry]]). It is well received, and he asks her to start writing a book about her experience, which she later titles '[[Brain on Fire]]'. Before the credits, text on screen confirms Susannah Catalan was the 217th person to be diagnosed with anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis, but her memoir has helped people all over the world, leading to thousands being diagnosed and treated since. She and Najjar remain close friends.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]] as [[Susannah Cahalan]], a 21-year-old woman who one day wakes up in restraints in a hospital a month after suffering from a mysterious illness that doctors are unable to diagnose<ref name=\"MoretzCast\" />\n* [[Jenny Slate]] as Margo, a friend and co-worker<ref name=\"MannSlateCast\" />\n* [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]] as Stephen, Cahalan's boyfriend<ref name=\"MannSlateCast\" />\n* [[Tyler Perry]] as Richard, Cahalan's boss at the ''[[New York Post]]''<ref name=\"PerryCast\" />\n* [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] as Rhona Nack, Cahalan's mother<ref name=\"MossArmitageCast\" /> \n* [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]] as Tom Cahalan, Cahalan's father<ref name=\"MossArmitageCast\" /> \n* [[Navid Negahban]] as Dr. [[Souhel Najjar]]\n* [[Alex Zahara]] as Allen\n* Jenn MacLean-Angus as Giselle\n\n== Production ==\nOn May 1, 2014, ''Deadline'' reported that [[Charlize Theron]] had acquired the film rights to [[Susannah Cahalan]]'s 2012 memoir ''[[Brain on Fire|Brain on Fire: My Month of Madness]]''.<ref name=May2014Deadline>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Charlize Theron Options 'Brain On Fire' As Star Vehicle For Dakota Fanning|url=https://deadline.com/2014/05/charlize-theron-options-brain-on-fire-as-star-vehicle-for-dakota-fanning-722889/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=May 1, 2014}}</ref> [[Dakota Fanning]] was set to play Cahalan, a young woman who one day wakes up in a hospital with no memory of the events of the previous month.<ref name=\"May2014Deadline\" /><ref name=Jan2013WP>{{cite news|last1=Scarf|first1=Maggie|title=BRAIN ON FIRE: My Month of Madness By Susannah Cahalan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/brain-on-fire-my-month-of-madness-by-susannah-cahalan/2013/01/12/d5e5ffcc-43c3-11e2-9648-a2c323a991d6_story.html|accessdate=July 21, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=The Washington Post Company|date=January 12, 2013}}</ref> Theron would produce along with Beth Kono and A.J. Dix through her banner [[Denver and Delilah Productions]].<ref name=\"May2014Deadline\" /> On January 22, 2015, [[Irish people|Irish]] filmmaker [[Gerard Barrett (director)|Gerard Barrett]] was set to write and direct the adaptation, while Rob Merilees of Foundation Features would produce and finance the film.<ref name=BarrettDirector>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title='Glassland' Helmer Gerard Barrett Set To Helm Dakota Fanning In Denver & Delilah-Produced 'Brain On Fire' \u2013 Sundance|url=https://deadline.com/2015/01/glassland-helmer-gerard-barrett-set-to-helm-dakota-fanning-in-denver-delilah-brain-on-fire-sundance-1201355563/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=January 22, 2015}}</ref> London-based Mister Smith Entertainment sold the film to international distributors at [[65th Berlin International Film Festival|2015 Berlin Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barraclough|first1=Leo|title=Mister Smith Launches Dakota Fanning Starrer 'Brain on Fire'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/mister-smith-launches-dakota-fanning-starrer-brain-of-fire-1201418322/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=January 29, 2015}}</ref> [[Will Poulter]] was added to the cast on February 4, 2015, to play Cahalan's boyfriend.<ref name=PoulterCast>{{cite news|last1=Barraclough|first1=Leo|title=Berlin: Will Poulter to Star Alongside Dakota Fanning in 'Brain on Fire'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/global/berlin-will-poulter-to-star-alongside-dakota-fanning-in-brain-on-fire-1201423432/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=February 4, 2015}}</ref> On May 26, 2015, [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]] and [[Jenny Slate]] were reportedly in talks to join the film, where Mann would play Cahalan's boyfriend, replacing Poulter.<ref name=MannSlateCast>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Thomas Mann, Jenny Slate Join 'Brain On Fire'; Dakota Fanning Stars In Woman's Descent Into Madness|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/thomas-mann-jenny-slate-brain-on-fire-dakota-fanning-susannah-cahalan-1201432909/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=May 26, 2015}}</ref> On June 26, 2015, it was announced that Dakota Fanning had left the project due to scheduling issues, and [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]] replaced her for the lead role.<ref name=MoretzCast>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Chloe Grace Moretz to Star in 'Brain on Fire' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chloe-grace-moretz-star-brain-805285|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=June 26, 2015}}</ref> On July 7, 2015, it was announced that [[Broad Green Pictures]] had come on board to produce and finance the film as well as distribute the film in the United States, while Lindsay Macadam would also produce along with producing partner Merilees.<ref name=July2015THR>{{cite news|last1=Kilday|first1=Gregg|title=Broad Green to Produce Chloe Grace Moretz Starrer 'Brain on Fire'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chloe-grace-moretz-brain-fire-807150|accessdate=July 19, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=July 13, 2015}}</ref> On July 16, 2015, [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] and [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]] were cast as Cahalan's parents, Rhona Nack and Tom Cahalan, respectively.<ref name=MossArmitageCast>{{cite news|last1=Jaafar|first1=Ali|title=Carrie-Anne Moss And Richard Armitage Board 'Brain On Fire' Opposite Chloe Grace Moretz|url=https://deadline.com/2015/07/carrie-anne-moss-chloe-grace-moretz-brain-on-fire-richard-armitage-1201477208/|accessdate=July 19, 2015|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> On July 20, 2015, [[Tyler Perry]] joined the film to play Richard, Cahalan's boss at the ''[[New York Post]]''.<ref name=PerryCast>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Tyler Perry Joins Chloe Moretz, Jenny Slate in 'Brain on Fire'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/tyler-perry-joins-chloe-moretz-jenny-slate-in-brain-on-fire/|accessdate=July 21, 2015|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began on July 13, 2015 in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"MossArmitageCast\"/><ref name=\"July2015THR\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=On the Set for 7/13/15: Jennifer Garner Begins Shooting Miracles from Heaven, Michael Bay Wraps 13 Hours & Doug Liman Calls Cut on Mena|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-71315-jennifer-garner-begins-shooting-miracles-from-heaven-michael-bay-wraps-13-hours-doug-liman-calls-cut-on-mena/|accessdate=July 14, 2015|work=SSN Insider|author=SSN Insider Staff|date=July 13, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403001444/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-71315-jennifer-garner-begins-shooting-miracles-from-heaven-michael-bay-wraps-13-hours-doug-liman-calls-cut-on-mena/#|archivedate=2016-04-03}}</ref> Moretz was spotted filming at the [[Vancouver General Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Scott|title=Actress Chloe Grace Moretz researches for 'Brain on Fire' at VGH|url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/movie-guide/Actress+Chloe+Grace+Moretz+researches+Brain+Fire/11220284/story.html|accessdate=July 21, 2015|work=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|publisher=[[Postmedia Network]]|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> Production on the film concluded on August 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=On the Set for 8/7/15: Katie Holmes Directs Her First Feature 'All We Had', Chloe Grace Moretz Finishes 'Brain on Fire'|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-8715-katie-holmes-directs-her-first-feature-all-we-had-chloe-grace-moretz-finishes-brain-on-fire/|accessdate=June 22, 2018|work=SSN Insider|author=SSN Insider Staff|date=August 7, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009080735/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-8715-katie-holmes-directs-her-first-feature-all-we-had-chloe-grace-moretz-finishes-brain-on-fire/#|archivedate=2016-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 14, 2016.<ref name=\"Brain on Fire\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/toronto-film-festival-completes-dance-card-terry-georges-the-promise-liev-schreiber-chuck-wepner-pic-the-bleeder-among-them-1201804129/|title=Toronto Fest Rounds Dance Card: Terry George's 'The Promise,' Liev Schreiber In 'The Bleeder,' Terrence Malick Docu Among Pics|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first=Mike Jr.|last=Fleming|date=August 16, 2016|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> Shortly after, [[Netflix]] acquired distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/02/broad-green-lucy-walker-buena-vista-social-club-step-sister-documentary-1201780636/|title=\nBroad Green Pictures Is Missing Release Dates and Angering Filmmakers. Here's Why.|website=[[IndieWire]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first1=Anne|last1=Thompson|first2=Graham|last2=Winfrey|date=February 17, 2017|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> It was released on June 22, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/2018/05/199977/netflix-new-releases-june-2018|title=Everything Coming To Netflix In June|website=[[Refinery29]]|first=Rebecca|last=Farley|date=May 23, 2018|accessdate=May 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 13%, based on 16 critics, and an average rating of 4.53/10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/brain_on_fire |title=Brain on Fire (2016) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] |accessdate=June 27, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 34 out of 100, based on 5 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/brain-on-fire |title=Brain on Fire Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|3704700}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|brain_on_fire}}\n\n{{Gerard Barrett}}\n\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Irish films]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films about mental disability]]\n[[Category:Films about diseases]]\n[[Category:Films about journalists]]\n[[Category:Films about writers]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about journalists]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about writers]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Canadian biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Irish biographical films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Irish drama films]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Broad Green Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Netflix original films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Gerard Barrett]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Charlize Theron]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Brain on Fire\n| image          = Brain on Fire.jpg\n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Gerard Barrett (director)|Gerard Barrett]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* A.J. Dix \n* Beth Kono \n* Rob Merilees \n*  Lindsay Macadam \n* [[Charlize Theron]]\n}}\n| writer         = Gerard Barrett\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Brain on Fire]]''|[[Susannah Cahalan]]}}\n| starring       =  {{Plainlist|\n* [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]] \n*  [[Jenny Slate]] \n*  [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]] \n* [[Tyler Perry]]\n*  [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] \n*  [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]]\n}}\n| music          = [[John Paesano]]\n| cinematography = Yaron Orbach\n| editing        = JC Bond\n| studio          =  {{Plainlist|\n*  [[Denver and Delilah Productions]]\n*  Foundation Features\n* [[Broad Green Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| released       = {{film date|2016|9|14|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2018|6|22|United States}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes<ref name=\"Brain on Fire\">{{cite web|url=http://tiff.net/films/brain-on-fire/|title=Brain on Fire|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n*  Canada\n*  Ireland \n* United States\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Brain on Fire''''' is a 2016 [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[drama]] film directed and written by [[Irish people|Irish]] filmmaker [[Gerard Barrett (director)|Gerard Barrett]]. The film is based on [[Susannah Cahalan]]'s memoir ''[[Brain on Fire|Brain on Fire: My Month of Madness]]'' and stars [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]], [[Jenny Slate]], [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]], [[Tyler Perry]], [[Carrie-Anne Moss]], and [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]]. The film follows a ''[[New York Post]]'' writer who begins to suffer a mysterious illness. [[Principal photography]] began on July 13, 2015, in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. After being evaluated extensively by many doctors, she was diagnosed to be psychotic. She would have been committed to psychiatric ward in a hospital and probably died of encephalitis, if it weren't for the efforts and skills of a Syrian-American neurologist( Souhel Najjar). He empathized with her case, was able to diagnose and treat her rare illness. It had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 14, 2016. The film was released on [[Netflix]] on June 22, 2018.\n\n== Plot ==\n21-year-old Susannah Cahalan ([[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]]) is a writer for ''[[The New York Post]]'' who lives with her new boyfriend Stephen ([[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]]). Susannah becomes suddenly ill, initially showing symptoms of a common flu like a cough and fatigue, but later begins presenting strange behaviour while in a trance state, such as hearing people say things they haven't said and hypersensitivity to loud noises.\n\nOver time, her behaviour becomes more and more erratic. Finally, Susannah suffers a seizure and seeks medical treatment. The doctor consulted is adamant it is down to Susannah parting too much, working too hard and not getting enough sleep. She moves in with her mother Rhona ([[Carrie-Anne Moss]]) and, after an emotional outburst, suffers another seizure, and is taken to a clinic where she undergoes an [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]]. Susannah also believes she may have [[bipolar disorder]] due to her severe mood changes.\n\nRhona struggles to care for Susannah, and she later moves in with her father Tom ([[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]]) and his new fianc\u00e9. During dinner one night, she becomes violent towards them while suffering another outburst, and her parents demand she is hospitalized despite the MRI, [[Electroencephalography|EEG]], and all other tests showing normal results. In the hospital, one the doctors informs Susannah's parents she could have [[schizophrenia]], and says that if her behaviour does not improve, she will be transferred to a psychiatric hospital. \n\nSusannah gradually becomes catatonic, and [[Souhel Najjar|Dr. Souhel Najjar]] ([[Navid Negahban]]) is asked to help in investigating her case. He has Susannah draw a clock; she draws it with all of the numbers (1\u201312) on the right side of the face, leading Najjar to believe that the right hemisphere of her brain is swollen and inflamed. Najjar has her undergo a brain biopsy in order to take cells from her brain for diagnosis. Following the biopsy, it is found that Susannah has a rare disease called [[anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis]], a brain inflammation, which Najjar describes as \"brain on fire\". Najjar begins treatment, which leads to a slow but full recovery of her cognitive abilities.\n\nSeven months later, Susannah is back at work. She presents her first written piece since her recovery to her boss Richard ([[Tyler Perry]]). It is well received, and he asks her to start writing a book about her experience, which she later titles '[[Brain on Fire]]'. Before the credits, text on screen confirms Susannah Catalan was the 217th person to be diagnosed with anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis, but her memoir has helped people all over the world, leading to thousands being diagnosed and treated since. She and Najjar remain close friends.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]] as [[Susannah Cahalan]], a 21-year-old woman who one day wakes up in restraints in a hospital a month after suffering from a mysterious illness that doctors are unable to diagnose<ref name=\"MoretzCast\" />\n* [[Jenny Slate]] as Margo, a friend and co-worker<ref name=\"MannSlateCast\" />\n* [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]] as Stephen, Cahalan's boyfriend<ref name=\"MannSlateCast\" />\n* [[Tyler Perry]] as Richard, Cahalan's boss at the ''[[New York Post]]''<ref name=\"PerryCast\" />\n* [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] as Rhona Nack, Cahalan's mother<ref name=\"MossArmitageCast\" /> \n* [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]] as Tom Cahalan, Cahalan's father<ref name=\"MossArmitageCast\" /> \n* [[Navid Negahban]] as Dr. [[Souhel Najjar]]\n* [[Alex Zahara]] as Allen\n* Jenn MacLean-Angus as Giselle\n\n== Production ==\nOn May 1, 2014, ''Deadline'' reported that [[Charlize Theron]] had acquired the film rights to [[Susannah Cahalan]]'s 2012 memoir ''[[Brain on Fire|Brain on Fire: My Month of Madness]]''.<ref name=May2014Deadline>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Charlize Theron Options 'Brain On Fire' As Star Vehicle For Dakota Fanning|url=https://deadline.com/2014/05/charlize-theron-options-brain-on-fire-as-star-vehicle-for-dakota-fanning-722889/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=May 1, 2014}}</ref> [[Dakota Fanning]] was set to play Cahalan, a young woman who one day wakes up in a hospital with no memory of the events of the previous month.<ref name=\"May2014Deadline\" /><ref name=Jan2013WP>{{cite news|last1=Scarf|first1=Maggie|title=BRAIN ON FIRE: My Month of Madness By Susannah Cahalan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/brain-on-fire-my-month-of-madness-by-susannah-cahalan/2013/01/12/d5e5ffcc-43c3-11e2-9648-a2c323a991d6_story.html|accessdate=July 21, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=The Washington Post Company|date=January 12, 2013}}</ref> Theron would produce along with Beth Kono and A.J. Dix through her banner [[Denver and Delilah Productions]].<ref name=\"May2014Deadline\" /> On January 22, 2015, [[Irish people|Irish]] filmmaker [[Gerard Barrett (director)|Gerard Barrett]] was set to write and direct the adaptation, while Rob Merilees of Foundation Features would produce and finance the film.<ref name=BarrettDirector>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title='Glassland' Helmer Gerard Barrett Set To Helm Dakota Fanning In Denver & Delilah-Produced 'Brain On Fire' \u2013 Sundance|url=https://deadline.com/2015/01/glassland-helmer-gerard-barrett-set-to-helm-dakota-fanning-in-denver-delilah-brain-on-fire-sundance-1201355563/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=January 22, 2015}}</ref> London-based Mister Smith Entertainment sold the film to international distributors at [[65th Berlin International Film Festival|2015 Berlin Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barraclough|first1=Leo|title=Mister Smith Launches Dakota Fanning Starrer 'Brain on Fire'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/mister-smith-launches-dakota-fanning-starrer-brain-of-fire-1201418322/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=January 29, 2015}}</ref> [[Will Poulter]] was added to the cast on February 4, 2015, to play Cahalan's boyfriend.<ref name=PoulterCast>{{cite news|last1=Barraclough|first1=Leo|title=Berlin: Will Poulter to Star Alongside Dakota Fanning in 'Brain on Fire'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/global/berlin-will-poulter-to-star-alongside-dakota-fanning-in-brain-on-fire-1201423432/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=February 4, 2015}}</ref> On May 26, 2015, [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]] and [[Jenny Slate]] were reportedly in talks to join the film, where Mann would play Cahalan's boyfriend, replacing Poulter.<ref name=MannSlateCast>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Thomas Mann, Jenny Slate Join 'Brain On Fire'; Dakota Fanning Stars In Woman's Descent Into Madness|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/thomas-mann-jenny-slate-brain-on-fire-dakota-fanning-susannah-cahalan-1201432909/|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=May 26, 2015}}</ref> On June 26, 2015, it was announced that Dakota Fanning had left the project due to scheduling issues, and [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]] replaced her for the lead role.<ref name=MoretzCast>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Chloe Grace Moretz to Star in 'Brain on Fire' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chloe-grace-moretz-star-brain-805285|accessdate=June 27, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=June 26, 2015}}</ref> On July 7, 2015, it was announced that [[Broad Green Pictures]] had come on board to produce and finance the film as well as distribute the film in the United States, while Lindsay Macadam would also produce along with producing partner Merilees.<ref name=July2015THR>{{cite news|last1=Kilday|first1=Gregg|title=Broad Green to Produce Chloe Grace Moretz Starrer 'Brain on Fire'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chloe-grace-moretz-brain-fire-807150|accessdate=July 19, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=July 13, 2015}}</ref> On July 16, 2015, [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] and [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]] were cast as Cahalan's parents, Rhona Nack and Tom Cahalan, respectively.<ref name=MossArmitageCast>{{cite news|last1=Jaafar|first1=Ali|title=Carrie-Anne Moss And Richard Armitage Board 'Brain On Fire' Opposite Chloe Grace Moretz|url=https://deadline.com/2015/07/carrie-anne-moss-chloe-grace-moretz-brain-on-fire-richard-armitage-1201477208/|accessdate=July 19, 2015|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> On July 20, 2015, [[Tyler Perry]] joined the film to play Richard, Cahalan's boss at the ''[[New York Post]]''.<ref name=PerryCast>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Tyler Perry Joins Chloe Moretz, Jenny Slate in 'Brain on Fire'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/tyler-perry-joins-chloe-moretz-jenny-slate-in-brain-on-fire/|accessdate=July 21, 2015|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began on July 13, 2015 in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"MossArmitageCast\"/><ref name=\"July2015THR\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=On the Set for 7/13/15: Jennifer Garner Begins Shooting Miracles from Heaven, Michael Bay Wraps 13 Hours & Doug Liman Calls Cut on Mena|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-71315-jennifer-garner-begins-shooting-miracles-from-heaven-michael-bay-wraps-13-hours-doug-liman-calls-cut-on-mena/|accessdate=July 14, 2015|work=SSN Insider|author=SSN Insider Staff|date=July 13, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403001444/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-71315-jennifer-garner-begins-shooting-miracles-from-heaven-michael-bay-wraps-13-hours-doug-liman-calls-cut-on-mena/#|archivedate=2016-04-03}}</ref> Moretz was spotted filming at the [[Vancouver General Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Scott|title=Actress Chloe Grace Moretz researches for 'Brain on Fire' at VGH|url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/movie-guide/Actress+Chloe+Grace+Moretz+researches+Brain+Fire/11220284/story.html|accessdate=July 21, 2015|work=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|publisher=[[Postmedia Network]]|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> Production on the film concluded on August 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=On the Set for 8/7/15: Katie Holmes Directs Her First Feature 'All We Had', Chloe Grace Moretz Finishes 'Brain on Fire'|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-8715-katie-holmes-directs-her-first-feature-all-we-had-chloe-grace-moretz-finishes-brain-on-fire/|accessdate=June 22, 2018|work=SSN Insider|author=SSN Insider Staff|date=August 7, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009080735/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-8715-katie-holmes-directs-her-first-feature-all-we-had-chloe-grace-moretz-finishes-brain-on-fire/#|archivedate=2016-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 14, 2016.<ref name=\"Brain on Fire\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/toronto-film-festival-completes-dance-card-terry-georges-the-promise-liev-schreiber-chuck-wepner-pic-the-bleeder-among-them-1201804129/|title=Toronto Fest Rounds Dance Card: Terry George's 'The Promise,' Liev Schreiber In 'The Bleeder,' Terrence Malick Docu Among Pics|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first=Mike Jr.|last=Fleming|date=August 16, 2016|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> Shortly after, [[Netflix]] acquired distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/02/broad-green-lucy-walker-buena-vista-social-club-step-sister-documentary-1201780636/|title=\nBroad Green Pictures Is Missing Release Dates and Angering Filmmakers. Here's Why.|website=[[IndieWire]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first1=Anne|last1=Thompson|first2=Graham|last2=Winfrey|date=February 17, 2017|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> It was released on June 22, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/2018/05/199977/netflix-new-releases-june-2018|title=Everything Coming To Netflix In June|website=[[Refinery29]]|first=Rebecca|last=Farley|date=May 23, 2018|accessdate=May 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 13%, based on 16 critics, and an average rating of 4.53/10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/brain_on_fire |title=Brain on Fire (2016) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] |accessdate=June 27, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 34 out of 100, based on 5 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/brain-on-fire |title=Brain on Fire Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|3704700}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|brain_on_fire}}\n\n{{Gerard Barrett}}\n\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Irish films]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films about mental disability]]\n[[Category:Films about diseases]]\n[[Category:Films about journalists]]\n[[Category:Films about writers]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about journalists]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about writers]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Canadian biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Irish biographical films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Irish drama films]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Broad Green Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Netflix original films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Gerard Barrett]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Charlize Theron]]\n", "name_user": "RaynHaze", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_on_Fire_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Timothy Corrigan (interior designer)", "text_new": "{{orphan|date=February 2011}}\n\n'''Timothy Corrigan''' is an [[interior designer]] with offices in [[Los Angeles]] and [[Paris]]. His firm, Timothy Corrigan, Inc., specializes in comfortably-elegant interior design and incorporates [[antiques]] into most of its projects. His clients include European and Middle Eastern royalty,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://designfile.architecturaldigest.com/search/title+of+article:The+Royal+Treatment|title=Home Decor - Decorating Ideas and House design - Architectural Digest|website=Architectural Digest}}</ref> Hollywood celebrities<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1stdibs.com/articles/the_talent/timothy_corrigan |title=The Talent: Timothy Corrigan |author=Sherrill, Marcia |publisher= 1stdibs|accessdate=2011-02-24 }}</ref> and corporate leaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstrepublic.com/clienttestimonials/timothy-corrigan-inc |title=Timothy Corrigan, Inc.; First Republic Bank |publisher=Firstrepublic.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCorrigan grew up in the [[Hancock Park]] neighborhood of Los Angeles, but moved with his family when he was 12. Decades later, for almost ten years he lived a mere five blocks from his childhood home. When he learned the property was on the market, he rushed over to see it, saying it \"was love at second sight.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=At home with Timothy Corrigan in Los Angeles |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VS7bXMiQv60 |website=YouTube |publisher=Quintessence |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2015-08-09}}</ref> He says he \"sent the owner a photo of me in the swimming pool when I was a little boy, with a note that said, 'Let me come home.'\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=Finn-Olaf |title=Timothy Corrigan's Los Angeles Home |journal=Architectural Digest |date=2012-04-01 |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/timothy-corrigan-los-angeles-home-article |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPrior to forming his design firm in 1998, Corrigan worked in [[advertising]] where he was president of international operations for Backer Speilvogel Bates Worldwide,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/27/business/the-media-business-advertising-addenda-backer-spielvogel-shifts-executives.html |newspaper=New York Times |title= Backer Spielvogel Shifts Executives |date=1993-04-27 |author=Elliott, Stuart |accessdate=2011-02-24 }}</ref> which later became [[Ted Bates (advertising firm)|Bates Worldwide]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/20/business/the-media-business-advertising-addenda-backer-spielvogel-to-change-its-name.html |title=Media Business |work=New York Times |accessdate=2011-02-25 |first=Stuart |last=Elliott |date=1994-04-20}}</ref> then Saatchi & Saatchi's Bates Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=http://www.timothy-corrigan.com/about-us.html |website=Timothy Corrigan |publisher=Timothy Corrigan, Inc. |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\nTimothy Corrigan is one of the world\u2019s leading interior designers[https://www.bestinteriordesigners.eu/top-interior-designers-timothy-corrigan/].With offices in Los Angeles and Paris his firm has completed projects in Europe, the Middle East and across the United States.  \n\nCorrigan has [https://www.amazon.com/s?k=the+new+elegance+timothy+corrigan&crid=M59EPICM1YUC&sprefix=the+new+elegance%2Caps%2C198&ref=nb_sb_ss_i_1_16 two best-selling books], published by Rizzoli: \u201cAn Invitation to Chateau du Grand-Luc\u00e9,\u201d that chronicles the restoration of his landmark chateau in France, and his second book, \u201cThe New Elegance: Stylish, Comfortable Rooms for Today\u201d that features 11 of Timothy\u2019s projects around the world, and highlights the building blocks for successful decoration.\n\n===Restoration===\nIn addition to restoring his childhood home, Corrigan has purchased and renovated several [[ch\u00e2teaux]] in [[France]]. He reportedly fell in love with the country the first time he traveled there in the 1980s.<ref name=LML181104 >{{cite news |title=This American is crazy about the Sarthe castles |url=https://www.lemainelibre.fr/actualite/sarthe-cet-americain-est-fou-des-chateaux-du-departement-13-05-2018-219628 |accessdate=2019-05-26 |agency=[[Le Maine libre]] |publisher=Les journaux de la Loire |date=2018-05-14}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the French government sold him the [https://chateaugrandluce.com/ Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9], located in [[Le Grand-Luc\u00e9]] within France's [[Loire Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |title=History - Hotel Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9 |url=https://chateaugrandluce.com/history/ |website=Hotel Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9 |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref> The ch\u00e2teau and its gardens are listed as French National Landmarks, which posed additional challenges during the renovation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/mersri_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00109770 |title=French National Landmarks}}</ref> His 2013 book, [https://www.rizzoliusa.com/book/9780847840946/ \"An Invitation to Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9\"], details Corrigan's against-all-odds acquisition of the 1764 manor that was in dire need of repair. His subsequent painstaking restoration and decoration brought it back to life as his private home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Eberstadt |first1=Fernanda |title=Timothy Corrigan's Spectacular French Ch\u00e2teau |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/timothy-corrigan-loire-valley-france-chateau-du-grand-luce-renovation |website=Architectural Digest - Renovation |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2015-11-06}}</ref> In 2016, Corrigan put the Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9 back on the market.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Montes |first1=Geoffrey |title=Timothy Corrigan Is Selling His Palatial French Ch\u00e2teau |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/timothy-corrigan-french-chateau |website=Architectural Digest |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2016-05-16}}</ref>\n\nIn spring of 2018, he purchased the Chateau de la Chevallerie, and began the renovation process.[https://quintessenceblog.com/at-home-with-timothy-corrigan-at-chateau-de-la-chevallerie-the-before/ At Home with Timothy Corrigan at Chateau de la Chevallerie]<ref name=LML181104 /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bewkes |first1=Stacey |title=At Home with Timothy Corrigan at Chateau de la Chevallerie (the before) |url=https://quintessenceblog.com/at-home-with-timothy-corrigan-at-chateau-de-la-chevallerie-the-before/ |website=Quintessence |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2018-11-04}}</ref>\n\n===Licensing===\nCorrigan designed the first fully integrated line of fabrics, trims, furniture, and floor covering for [https://www.fschumacher.com/browse/collections/timothy-corrigan Schumacher] and [https://pattersonflynnmartin.com/timothy-corrigan/ Patterson, Flynn & Martin], introduced in 2014. He has designed two tabletop collections for porcelain manufacturer [https://www.royal-limoges.fr/boutique_us/recherche_resultats.cfm?code_lg=lg_us&mot=corrigan Royal Limoges], a collection of high-end bathroom fittings and accessories for [https://www.thg-paris.com/ THG Paris],<ref>{{cite web |title=Timothy Corrigan Collections |url=https://www.thg-paris.com/international/en/designers/timothy-corrigan |website=THG Paris |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> a wallcovering collection for London-based [https://www.fromental.co.uk/ Fromental],<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Les Folies\", The Timothy Corrigan Collection |url=https://www.fromental.co.uk/collections/collaborations/les-folies-the-timothy-corrigan-collection/ |website=Fromental |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherman |first1=Rebecca |title=Timothy Corrigan for Fromental Wallpapers |url=http://www.housesgardenspeople.com/2019/02/timothy-corrigan-for-fromental.html |website=HousesGardensPeople |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> and a [[passementerie]] collection for [https://samuelandsons.com/products#action=updateSearchResults&type=results&sale=0&keywords=chevallerie&colorcode=&page=1 Samuel & Sons].\n\nHis latest projects include designs for luxury performance fabrics and rugs for [https://www.perennialsfabrics.com Perennials], and hide rugs for [https://kylebunting.com Kyle Bunting].\n\n==Press==\nCorrigan has been featured in numerous, prestigious publications including ''[[The Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brzezinski |first1=Victoria |title=Tastemakers: Timothy Corrigan, interior designer |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tastemakers-timothy-corrigan-interior-designer-fdhctnv7j |accessdate=2019-05-26 |agency=The Sunday Times |publisher=Times Newspapers Limited |date=2018-08-03}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Renzi |first1=Jen |title=Museum Quality: Enter the eclectic, cozy paean to 18th-century French style that shaped designer Timothy Corrigan |journal=The Wall Street Journal |date=2011-11-26 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203611404577046301337778484 |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref> ''[[Architectural Digest]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/search?sort=score+desc&qt=dismax&query=timothy+corrigan&submitbtn.x=0&submitbtn.y=0&submitbtn=Submit |title=Timothy Corrigan |website=Architectural Digest |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast Digital|accessdate=2011-02-24 }}</ref> ''[[Elle Decor|ELLE D\u00e9cor]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://find.elledecor.com/search/timothy-corrigan/ |title=Timothy Corrigan |work=ELLE D\u00e9cor |publisher=Hachette Fillapacchi Media U.S., INC |accessdate=2011-02-25}}</ref> [http://www.pointdevue.fr/ ''Point de Vue''],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Silamo |first1=Sabrina |title=Universe. At Timothy Corrigan in Paris |journal=Point de Vue Magazine |date=2018-05-29 |issue=Update 2018\u201311\u201305 |url=http://www.pointdevue.fr/art-de-vivre/univers-chez-timothy-corrigan-paris_5763.html |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=BY THE NUMBERS Tim Corrigan |date=2011-11-26 |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/11/13/t-magazine/by-the-numbers-tim-corrigan.html |website=T Magazine (The New York Times Style Magazine) |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> ''[[InStyle]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jackson |first1=Eric |last2=Salazar |first2=Angela |title=Tip-Top Tables |journal=InStyle |date=2007-11-01 |url=http://www.timothy-corrigan.com/press/2007/11/01/90-instyle |accessdate=2019-05-26 |publisher=Meredith Corporation}}</ref> ''[[Traditional Home]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.traditionalhome.com/design_decorating/howwelive/hollywood-regency-remodel_ss1.html |author=Elbert, Amy |title=Hollywood Before & After |work=Traditional Home |publisher=Meredith Corporation  |accessdate=2011-02-25}}</ref> and ''[[Town & Country (magazine)|Town & Country]]''.<ref>Rafferty, Jean Bond. French Lessons, Town & Country, April 2005, Hearst Communications, Inc.</ref> He has also appeared on national and international television, including on [[HGTV]]\u2019s ''Million Dollar Rooms'', HGTV\u2019s ''Top Ten'', LXTV\u2019s ''International Open House \u2013 Paris'',<ref>{{cite web |title=LXTV \"International Open House\" Paris |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O3f9Y_z1gTE |website=YouTube |publisher=Timothy Corrigan |accessdate=2019-05-26 |archivedate=2010-12-09 |date=2010-12-01}}</ref> and ''[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hgtv.com/video/chateau-du-grand-luce-video/index.html |title=Chateau du Grand-Luce |publisher=HGTV |accessdate=2011-02-25 }}</ref> He was chosen to design the ''Architectural Digest'' [[Greenroom|green room]] at the 59th [[Primetime Emmy Awards]].\n\n==Awards==\nCorrigan has been honored by design centers around the world and named to multiple top designer lists:\n* ''Architectural Digest'' AD100 (World's Top Interior Designers and Architects); the only one of nine designers who were consecutively on the list since 2007 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/timothy-corrigan-inc-ad100#package|title=Timothy Corrigan Inc.- AD100 2016 |website=Architectural Digest |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast}}</ref>\n* ''Luxe Interiors + Design'' 2019 Gold List <ref>{{cite web |title=2019 Gold List |url=https://luxedaily.luxesource.com/2019-gold-list-interior-design/#.XOpw3yBKhpg |website=Luxe Interiors + Design |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n* 2017 ''ELLE D\u00e9cor'' A-List <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.elledecor.com/design-decorate/interior-designers/g3076/a-list-interior-designers/?slide=23 | title=The 2019 a List: 100+ of ELLE DECOR's Favorite Interior Designers| date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n* 2017 Design Icon, during the Winter [[Las Vegas Market]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Timothy Corrigan, Design Icon 2017 |url=https://www.lasvegasmarket.com/for-attendees/design/w17/design-icon-2017-announced |website=Las Vegas Market |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n* ''Luxe Interiors + Design'' 2017 & 2019 Gold List <ref>{{cite web |title=2017 Gold List |url=https://luxesource.com/gold-list/2017/interior-design |website=Luxe Interiors + Design |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n* 2014 \"Star of Design\" Award for Interior Design, [[Pacific Design Center]] in West Hollywood, CA <ref>{{cite web |title=WESTWEEK 2014 Delivers Best-in-Class Design |url=https://www.pacificdesigncenter.com/2014/03/westweek-2014-delivers-best-class-design/ |website=Pacific Design Center |publisher=Cohen Design Centers |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n* Robb Report's Top 40 Interior Designers in the World, 2007 <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.timothy-corrigan.com/press/2007/06/01/70-robb-report-luxury-home | title=Press - Interior Design News - Robb Report Luxury Home, June 2007 - Timothy Corrigan}}</ref>\n\n* Corrigan is the only American designer honored by the [http://frenchheritagesociety.org French Heritage Society], for his restoration work of landmark buildings in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://editoratlarge.com/articles/event-recap-french-heritage-society-honors-corrigan-hermes|title=Event Recap: French Heritage Society honors Corrigan, Herm\u00e8s|publisher=|date=2014-11-21}}</ref> \n\n* Corrigan was honored by [[The Institute of Classical Architecture and Art]] (ICAA, Southern California Chapter) at their annual Legacy Dinner in October 2018, for his achievements and contributions in advancing the classical tradition in architecture and art.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tribute Video & Photos - 2018 Legacy Dinner Honoring Timothy Corrigan |url=http://classicist-socal.org/announcements/tribute-video-photos-2018-legacy-dinner-honoring-timothy-corrigan |website=Institute of Classical Architecture & Art |publisher=ICAA Southern California |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2018-04-24}}</ref> \n\n* Named to the ''Departures'' Design Council in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=DEPARTURES Design Council |url=https://access.departures.com/design-council/ |website=DEPARTURES |publisher=Meredith Corporation Travel & Leisure Group |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Timothy Corrigan, Inc. - Access DEPARTURES |url=https://access.departures.com/design-council/timothy-corrigan-inc/ |website=DEPARTURES |publisher=Meredith Corporation Travel & Leisure Group |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n* 2019 1stDibs 50: From their unique approach to the craft to their ability to create one-of-a-kind spaces, these designers are leading by example in 2019. [https://www.1stdibs.com/design-firms/the-1stdibs-50/]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.timothy-corrigan.com}}\n* [http://www.rizzoliusa.com/book.php?isbn=9780847840946 Rizzoli, New York]<references group=\"porcelain\" />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corrigan, Timothy}}\n[[Category:American interior designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{orphan|date=February 2011}}\n\n'''Timothy Corrigan''' is an [[interior designer]] with offices in [[Los Angeles]] and [[Paris]]. His firm, Timothy Corrigan, Inc., specializes in comfortably-elegant interior design and incorporates [[antiques]] into most of its projects. His clients include European and Middle Eastern royalty,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://designfile.architecturaldigest.com/search/title+of+article:The+Royal+Treatment|title=Home Decor - Decorating Ideas and House design - Architectural Digest|website=Architectural Digest}}</ref> Hollywood celebrities<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1stdibs.com/articles/the_talent/timothy_corrigan |title=The Talent: Timothy Corrigan |author=Sherrill, Marcia |publisher= 1stdibs|accessdate=2011-02-24 }}</ref> and corporate leaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstrepublic.com/clienttestimonials/timothy-corrigan-inc |title=Timothy Corrigan, Inc.; First Republic Bank |publisher=Firstrepublic.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCorrigan grew up in the [[Hancock Park]] neighborhood of Los Angeles, but moved with his family when he was 12. Decades later, for almost ten years he lived a mere five blocks from his childhood home. When he learned the property was on the market, he rushed over to see it, saying it \"was love at second sight.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=At home with Timothy Corrigan in Los Angeles |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VS7bXMiQv60 |website=YouTube |publisher=Quintessence |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2015-08-09}}</ref> He says he \"sent the owner a photo of me in the swimming pool when I was a little boy, with a note that said, 'Let me come home.'\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=Finn-Olaf |title=Timothy Corrigan's Los Angeles Home |journal=Architectural Digest |date=2012-04-01 |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/timothy-corrigan-los-angeles-home-article |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPrior to forming his design firm in 1998, Corrigan worked in [[advertising]] where he was president of international operations for Backer Speilvogel Bates Worldwide,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/27/business/the-media-business-advertising-addenda-backer-spielvogel-shifts-executives.html |newspaper=New York Times |title= Backer Spielvogel Shifts Executives |date=1993-04-27 |author=Elliott, Stuart |accessdate=2011-02-24 }}</ref> which later became [[Ted Bates (advertising firm)|Bates Worldwide]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/20/business/the-media-business-advertising-addenda-backer-spielvogel-to-change-its-name.html |title=Media Business |work=New York Times |accessdate=2011-02-25 |first=Stuart |last=Elliott |date=1994-04-20}}</ref> then Saatchi & Saatchi's Bates Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=http://www.timothy-corrigan.com/about-us.html |website=Timothy Corrigan |publisher=Timothy Corrigan, Inc. |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\nTimothy Corrigan is one of the world\u2019s leading interior designers[https://www.bestinteriordesigners.eu/top-interior-designers-timothy-corrigan/].With offices in Los Angeles and Paris his firm has completed projects in Europe, the Middle East and across the United States.  \n\nCorrigan has [https://www.amazon.com/s?k=the+new+elegance+timothy+corrigan&crid=M59EPICM1YUC&sprefix=the+new+elegance%2Caps%2C198&ref=nb_sb_ss_i_1_16 two best-selling books], published by Rizzoli: \u201cAn Invitation to Chateau du Grand-Luc\u00e9,\u201d that chronicles the restoration of his landmark chateau in France, and his second book, \u201cThe New Elegance: Stylish, Comfortable Rooms for Today\u201d that features 11 of Timothy\u2019s projects around the world, and highlights the building blocks for successful decoration.\n\n===Restoration===\nIn addition to restoring his childhood home, Corrigan has purchased and renovated several [[ch\u00e2teaux]] in [[France]]. He reportedly fell in love with the country the first time he traveled there in the 1980s.<ref name=LML181104 >{{cite news |title=This American is crazy about the Sarthe castles |url=https://www.lemainelibre.fr/actualite/sarthe-cet-americain-est-fou-des-chateaux-du-departement-13-05-2018-219628 |accessdate=2019-05-26 |agency=[[Le Maine libre]] |publisher=Les journaux de la Loire |date=2018-05-14}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the French government sold him the [https://chateaugrandluce.com/ Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9], located in [[Le Grand-Luc\u00e9]] within France's [[Loire Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |title=History - Hotel Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9 |url=https://chateaugrandluce.com/history/ |website=Hotel Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9 |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref> The ch\u00e2teau and its gardens are listed as French National Landmarks, which posed additional challenges during the renovation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/mersri_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00109770 |title=French National Landmarks}}</ref> His 2013 book, [https://www.rizzoliusa.com/book/9780847840946/ \"An Invitation to Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9\"], details Corrigan's against-all-odds acquisition of the 1764 manor that was in dire need of repair. His subsequent painstaking restoration and decoration brought it back to life as his private home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Eberstadt |first1=Fernanda |title=Timothy Corrigan's Spectacular French Ch\u00e2teau |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/timothy-corrigan-loire-valley-france-chateau-du-grand-luce-renovation |website=Architectural Digest - Renovation |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2015-11-06}}</ref> In 2016, Corrigan put the Ch\u00e2teau du Grand-Luc\u00e9 back on the market.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Montes |first1=Geoffrey |title=Timothy Corrigan Is Selling His Palatial French Ch\u00e2teau |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/timothy-corrigan-french-chateau |website=Architectural Digest |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2016-05-16}}</ref>\n\nIn spring of 2018, he purchased the Chateau de la Chevallerie, and began the renovation process.<ref name=LML181104 /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bewkes |first1=Stacey |title=At Home with Timothy Corrigan at Chateau de la Chevallerie (the before) |url=https://quintessenceblog.com/at-home-with-timothy-corrigan-at-chateau-de-la-chevallerie-the-before/ |website=Quintessence |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2018-11-04}}</ref>\n\n===Licensing===\nCorrigan designed the first fully integrated line of fabrics, trims, furniture, and floor covering for [https://www.fschumacher.com/browse/collections/timothy-corrigan Schumacher] and [https://pattersonflynnmartin.com/timothy-corrigan/ Patterson, Flynn & Martin], introduced in 2014. He has designed two tabletop collections for porcelain manufacturer [https://www.royal-limoges.fr/boutique_us/recherche_resultats.cfm?code_lg=lg_us&mot=corrigan Royal Limoges], a collection of high-end bathroom fittings and accessories for [https://www.thg-paris.com/ THG Paris],<ref>{{cite web |title=Timothy Corrigan Collections |url=https://www.thg-paris.com/international/en/designers/timothy-corrigan |website=THG Paris |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> a wallcovering collection for London-based [https://www.fromental.co.uk/ Fromental],<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Les Folies\", The Timothy Corrigan Collection |url=https://www.fromental.co.uk/collections/collaborations/les-folies-the-timothy-corrigan-collection/ |website=Fromental |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherman |first1=Rebecca |title=Timothy Corrigan for Fromental Wallpapers |url=http://www.housesgardenspeople.com/2019/02/timothy-corrigan-for-fromental.html |website=HousesGardensPeople |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> and a [[passementerie]] collection for [https://samuelandsons.com/products#action=updateSearchResults&type=results&sale=0&keywords=chevallerie&colorcode=&page=1 Samuel & Sons].\n\nHis latest projects include designs for luxury performance fabrics and rugs for [https://www.perennialsfabrics.com Perennials], and hide rugs for [https://kylebunting.com Kyle Bunting].\n\n==Press==\nCorrigan has been featured in numerous, prestigious publications including ''[[The Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brzezinski |first1=Victoria |title=Tastemakers: Timothy Corrigan, interior designer |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tastemakers-timothy-corrigan-interior-designer-fdhctnv7j |accessdate=2019-05-26 |agency=The Sunday Times |publisher=Times Newspapers Limited |date=2018-08-03}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Renzi |first1=Jen |title=Museum Quality: Enter the eclectic, cozy paean to 18th-century French style that shaped designer Timothy Corrigan |journal=The Wall Street Journal |date=2011-11-26 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203611404577046301337778484 |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref> ''[[Architectural Digest]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/search?sort=score+desc&qt=dismax&query=timothy+corrigan&submitbtn.x=0&submitbtn.y=0&submitbtn=Submit |title=Timothy Corrigan |website=Architectural Digest |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast Digital|accessdate=2011-02-24 }}</ref> ''[[Elle Decor|ELLE D\u00e9cor]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://find.elledecor.com/search/timothy-corrigan/ |title=Timothy Corrigan |work=ELLE D\u00e9cor |publisher=Hachette Fillapacchi Media U.S., INC |accessdate=2011-02-25}}</ref> [http://www.pointdevue.fr/ ''Point de Vue''],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Silamo |first1=Sabrina |title=Universe. At Timothy Corrigan in Paris |journal=Point de Vue Magazine |date=2018-05-29 |issue=Update 2018\u201311\u201305 |url=http://www.pointdevue.fr/art-de-vivre/univers-chez-timothy-corrigan-paris_5763.html |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=BY THE NUMBERS Tim Corrigan |date=2011-11-26 |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/11/13/t-magazine/by-the-numbers-tim-corrigan.html |website=T Magazine (The New York Times Style Magazine) |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> ''[[InStyle]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jackson |first1=Eric |last2=Salazar |first2=Angela |title=Tip-Top Tables |journal=InStyle |date=2007-11-01 |url=http://www.timothy-corrigan.com/press/2007/11/01/90-instyle |accessdate=2019-05-26 |publisher=Meredith Corporation}}</ref> ''[[Traditional Home]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.traditionalhome.com/design_decorating/howwelive/hollywood-regency-remodel_ss1.html |author=Elbert, Amy |title=Hollywood Before & After |work=Traditional Home |publisher=Meredith Corporation  |accessdate=2011-02-25}}</ref> and ''[[Town & Country (magazine)|Town & Country]]''.<ref>Rafferty, Jean Bond. French Lessons, Town & Country, April 2005, Hearst Communications, Inc.</ref> He has also appeared on national and international television, including on [[HGTV]]\u2019s ''Million Dollar Rooms'', HGTV\u2019s ''Top Ten'', LXTV\u2019s ''International Open House \u2013 Paris'',<ref>{{cite web |title=LXTV \"International Open House\" Paris |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O3f9Y_z1gTE |website=YouTube |publisher=Timothy Corrigan |accessdate=2019-05-26 |archivedate=2010-12-09 |date=2010-12-01}}</ref> and ''[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hgtv.com/video/chateau-du-grand-luce-video/index.html |title=Chateau du Grand-Luce |publisher=HGTV |accessdate=2011-02-25 }}</ref> He was chosen to design the ''Architectural Digest'' [[Greenroom|green room]] at the 59th [[Primetime Emmy Awards]].\n\n==Awards==\nCorrigan has been honored by design centers around the world and named to multiple top designer lists:\n* ''Architectural Digest'' AD100 (World's Top Interior Designers and Architects); the only one of nine designers who were consecutively on the list since 2007 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/timothy-corrigan-inc-ad100#package|title=Timothy Corrigan Inc.- AD100 2016 |website=Architectural Digest |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast}}</ref>\n* ''Luxe Interiors + Design'' 2019 Gold List <ref>{{cite web |title=2019 Gold List |url=https://luxedaily.luxesource.com/2019-gold-list-interior-design/#.XOpw3yBKhpg |website=Luxe Interiors + Design |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n* 2017 ''ELLE D\u00e9cor'' A-List <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.elledecor.com/design-decorate/interior-designers/g3076/a-list-interior-designers/?slide=23 | title=The 2019 a List: 100+ of ELLE DECOR's Favorite Interior Designers| date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n* 2017 Design Icon, during the Winter [[Las Vegas Market]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Timothy Corrigan, Design Icon 2017 |url=https://www.lasvegasmarket.com/for-attendees/design/w17/design-icon-2017-announced |website=Las Vegas Market |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n* ''Luxe Interiors + Design'' 2017 & 2019 Gold List <ref>{{cite web |title=2017 Gold List |url=https://luxesource.com/gold-list/2017/interior-design |website=Luxe Interiors + Design |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n* 2014 \"Star of Design\" Award for Interior Design, [[Pacific Design Center]] in West Hollywood, CA <ref>{{cite web |title=WESTWEEK 2014 Delivers Best-in-Class Design |url=https://www.pacificdesigncenter.com/2014/03/westweek-2014-delivers-best-class-design/ |website=Pacific Design Center |publisher=Cohen Design Centers |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n* Robb Report's Top 40 Interior Designers in the World, 2007 <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.timothy-corrigan.com/press/2007/06/01/70-robb-report-luxury-home | title=Press - Interior Design News - Robb Report Luxury Home, June 2007 - Timothy Corrigan}}</ref>\n\n* Corrigan is the only American designer honored by the [http://frenchheritagesociety.org French Heritage Society], for his restoration work of landmark buildings in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://editoratlarge.com/articles/event-recap-french-heritage-society-honors-corrigan-hermes|title=Event Recap: French Heritage Society honors Corrigan, Herm\u00e8s|publisher=|date=2014-11-21}}</ref> \n\n* Corrigan was honored by [[The Institute of Classical Architecture and Art]] (ICAA, Southern California Chapter) at their annual Legacy Dinner in October 2018, for his achievements and contributions in advancing the classical tradition in architecture and art.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tribute Video & Photos - 2018 Legacy Dinner Honoring Timothy Corrigan |url=http://classicist-socal.org/announcements/tribute-video-photos-2018-legacy-dinner-honoring-timothy-corrigan |website=Institute of Classical Architecture & Art |publisher=ICAA Southern California |accessdate=2019-05-25 |date=2018-04-24}}</ref> \n\n* Named to the ''Departures'' Design Council in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=DEPARTURES Design Council |url=https://access.departures.com/design-council/ |website=DEPARTURES |publisher=Meredith Corporation Travel & Leisure Group |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Timothy Corrigan, Inc. - Access DEPARTURES |url=https://access.departures.com/design-council/timothy-corrigan-inc/ |website=DEPARTURES |publisher=Meredith Corporation Travel & Leisure Group |accessdate=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n* 2019 1stDibs 50: From their unique approach to the craft to their ability to create one-of-a-kind spaces, these designers are leading by example in 2019. [https://www.1stdibs.com/design-firms/the-1stdibs-50/]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.timothy-corrigan.com}}\n* [http://www.rizzoliusa.com/book.php?isbn=9780847840946 Rizzoli, New York]<references group=\"porcelain\" />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corrigan, Timothy}}\n[[Category:American interior designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Elainerm", "label": "safe", "comment": "link added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timothy_Corrigan_(interior_designer)"}
{"title_page": "CDHS experiment", "text_new": "[[File:The CDHS (WA1) experimental setup.jpg|thumb|The CDHS (WA1) experimental setup at CERN]]\n\n'''CDHS''' was a neutrino experiment at CERN taking data from 1976 until 1984. The experiment was officially referred to as ''WA1''. CDHS was a collaboration of groups from [[CERN]], [[Technical University Dortmund|Dortmund]], [[Heidelberg University|Heidelberg]], [[Saclay]] and later [[Warsaw]]. The collaboration was led by [[Jack Steinberger]]. The experiment was designed to study [[deep inelastic scattering|deep inelastic]] [[neutrino]] interactions in iron.\n\n== Experimental setup ==\n[[File:Technical sketch of the upgraded CDHS detector.png|thumb|Technical sketch of the upgraded CDHS detector]]\nThe core of the detector consisted of 19 (later 20) magnetized iron modules. In the spacings between these, [[wire chamber #Drift chambers|drift chambers]] for track reconstruction were installed. Additionally, plastic [[scintillator|scintillators]] were inserted into the iron. Each iron module therefore served successively as an interaction target, where the neutrinos hit and produced [[particle shower #hadronic showers|hadron showers]], a calorimeter that measured those hadrons' energy and a spectrometer, determining the momenta of produced [[muon]]s via magnetic deflection.<ref name=annual>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/1479923?ln=en CERN Document Server: Annual Report 1976 (Experimental Physics Division)] Retrieved on 14 August 2018</ref><ref name=detector/>\n\nAt the time of its completion in 1976, the overall detector was 20 m long and weighed approximately 1250 tons.\n\nThe experiment was located in CERN's [[List_of_Super_Proton_Synchrotron_experiments#WA experiments|West Area]], in building 182. The [[neutrinos]] (and antineutrinos) were produced by protons from the [[Super Proton Synchrotron]] (SPS) at energies of around 400 GeV, which were shot onto a [[beryllium]] target.<ref name=annual/>\n\n== History ==\nThe experiment was first proposed in July 1973 by a group led by [[Jack Steinberger]] as a two-piece detector. The front should serve as the [[neutrino]] target and [[particle shower #hadronic showers|hadronic shower]] detector, the following second part should detect the [[muon]] traces.<ref name=proposal>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/604411?ln=en CERN Document Server: Proposal to study high-energy neutrino interactions at the SPS] Retrieved on 13 August 2018</ref> It was planned that the four proposing groups from Saclay, Dortmund, Heidelberg and CERN would contribute with complementary expertise and manpower. For example, Saclay was assigned to be in charge of the [[wire chamber #Drift chambers|drift chambers]], whereas CERN should handle the iron core magnets. It were also these four groups that gave the experiment its name: '''''C'''ERN '''D'''ortmund '''H'''eidelberg '''S'''aclay (CDHS)''.\nApproximately 30 people should form the final experiment group.<ref name=memorandum>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/604399?ln=en CERN Document Server: Memorandum following up the proposal] Retrieved on 13 August 2018</ref> \n\nAfter prolongued discussions with the SPS Committee, that was in charge of approving the proposals and distributing available money, an updated proposal for the new detector was submitted in March 1974. The suggested detector was a modular setup consisting of magnetized [[iron]] modules in combination with [[wire chamber #Drift chambers|drift chambers]] and plastic [[scintillator|scintillators]].<ref name=memo74> [https://cds.cern.ch/record/594735?ln=en CERN Document Server: Memorandum - design and physics of the proposed muon spectrometer] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref> This new proposal was approved by the committee in April 1974. Construction started soon after and was completed in 1976. The experiment's official name was ''WA1'', since it was the first approved experiment at CERN's [[List_of_Super_Proton_Synchrotron_experiments#WA experiments|West Area]].\nThe estimated cost of the detector ranged between 6 and 8 million [[Swiss franc|CHF]].<ref name=proposal/> \n\nIn 1979, an upgrade of the experimental setup was proposed.<ref>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/596902?ln=en CERN Document Server:  Request for approval of WA1 improvement programme] Retrieved on 14 August 2018</ref> The main reason for this upgrade was the comparably low resolution of eight of the 19 detector modules. This situation should be improved by inserting twelve new and better modules, resulting in a slightly longer and significantly more accurate machine. The proposal also included the suggestion for a group from [[Warsaw University]], led by Adam Para, to join the project. \nStarting with the long shutdown of the [[Super Proton Synchrotron]] (SPS) from summer 1980 on, the requested changes were implemented. Eventually, half of the experiment's target calorimeters got replaced and the total number of detector modules was increased from 19 to 20. This led to four times higher spatial resolution of the produced particles as well as 25 % more accurate measurements of the deposited hadronic energy. Additionally, four new drift chambers were installed, improving the reconstruction of [[muon]] tracks.<ref>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/1720097?ln=en CERN Document Server:  New developments at WA1 (CERN Bulletin Issue No. 7/1982)] Retrieved on 14 August 2018</ref><ref name=new>[https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01555493 P. Berge et al.: A measurement of differential cross-sections and nucleon structure functions in charged-current neutrino interactions on iron] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref> Later, a liquid [[hydrogen]] tank was added in front of the detector as a target to measure the [[structure function]] of [[proton]]s.<ref name=abra2>[https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01571954 H. Abramovicz et al.: Measurement of neutrino and antineutrino structure functions in hydrogen and iron] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref>\n\nCDHS took data with neutrinos delivered by the SPS from late 1976 until September 1984.\n\n== Results and discoveries ==\nThe scientific goal of the CDHS experiment was to study high energy neutrino interactions. When the incoming [[neutrino]]s (or antineutrinos) were interacting with the target [[iron]], either charged current ([[neutrino|{{SubatomicParticle|neutrino}}]] + [[iron|Fe]] \u2192 [[muon|{{SubatomicParticle|antimuon}}]] + anything) or [[neutral current]] ({{SubatomicParticle|neutrino}} + Fe \u2192 {{SubatomicParticle|neutrino}} + anything) events could be produced.<ref name=detector>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0029-554X(70)90173-4 M. Holder et al.: A detector for high-energy neutrino interactions] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref> \n\nOne of the main objectives of the experiment was to determine the ratio between the neutral and the charged inclusive neutrino [[Cross section (physics)|cross sections]], from which the [[Weinberg angle]] could be inferred.<ref name=highlights>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/2103282?ln=en CERN Document Server: W. D. Schlatter - Highlights from High Energy Neutrino Experiments at CERN] Retrieved on 14 August 2018</ref> [[Neutral currents]] had previously been discovered by the [[Gargamelle]] experiment, which had also provided first estimates of the Weinberg angle. The results were confirmed and measured with much higher precision by CDHS, allowing to predict the mass of the [[top quark]], before it was discovered at the [[Tevatron]], with approximately \u00b140 GeV precision.<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-2693(77)90783-3 M. Holder et al.: Measurement of the neutral to charged current cross section ratio in neutrino and antineutrino interactions] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref><ref name=highlights/> \n\nOther measurements regarding the [[electroweak interaction]] within the [[standard model]] included the measurement of more than one [[muon]]; i.e. dimuon and trimuon events.<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-2693(77)90685-2 M. Holder et al.: Observation of trimuon events produced in neutrino and antineutrino interactions] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref><ref>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-2693(78)90214-9 T. Hansl et al.: Origin of trimuon events in high-energy neutrino interactions] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref>\n\nResults obtained at CDHS provided experimental validation of the [[standard model]], at a time when this model was still in the testing phase. An important step in this regard was the falsification of the alleged \"high-y anomaly\". The value y characterizes the inelasticity of neutrino collisions, i.e. it measures the amount of energy that an incoming neutrino transfers to the [[hadron]]s during their collision. Experiments at [[Fermilab]] had found the so-called \"high-y anomaly\", which challenged the standard model. However, results from CDHS disproved those findings, strengthening the [[standard model]].<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.39.433 M. Holder et al.: Is There a High-y Anomaly in Antineutrino Interactions?] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref> \n\nCDHS examined the nucleon [[structure function]]s, which enabled scientists to confirm the theory of [[quantum chromodynamics]] (QCD).<ref name=abra>[https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01575772 H. Abramovicz: Tests of QCD and Non-Asymptotically-Free Theories of the Strong Interaction by an Analysis of the Nucleon Structure Functions <math>xF_3, F_2</math>, and {{SubatomicParticle|antiquark}} ] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref><ref name=new/> This work included the determination of the QCD [[coupling constant#QCD and asymptotic freedom|coupling constant]] <math> \\alpha_\\text{s}</math>, verification of the [[quark]]'s (s = {{sfrac|1|2}}) and [[gluon]]'s (s = 1) [[spin (physics)|spin]], as well as the falsification of both [[Gauge theory|abelian]] theories of [[strong interaction]]s and theories based on scalar gluons.<ref name=abra2/><ref name=abra/>\nAdditionally, the experiments provided insights into the structure of the [[nucleon]], examining the distribution of [[gluon]]s, [[quark]]s and [[antiquark]]s within it. Results from CDHS were in line with the [[Parton (particle physics)|quark parton model]], that assigned [[quark]]s to be point-like [[Parton (particle physics)|parton]]s.<ref name=highlights/>. In this context, it was also confirmed that the number of [[valence quark]]s in a [[nucleon]] is 3.<ref>[http://ep-news.web.cern.ch/content/interview-philippe-bloch CERN Newsletter of the EP Department: Interview with Philippe Bloch ] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref> Finally, the CDHS results allowed to determine the [[momentum]] distribution of [[strange quark]]s and antiquarks within a [[nucleon]].<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01573422 H. Abramovicz et al.: Experimental Study of Opposite-Sign Dimuons Produced in Neutrino and Antineutrino Interactions ] Retrieved on 17 August 2018</ref> \n\nDuring its last years of operation, the CDHS collaboration engaged in the search for [[neutrino oscillation]]s. Although this phenomenon could not be confirmed using CERN's large energy neutrino beam, this attempt influenced the following experiments that eventually discovered [[neutrino oscillation]]s.<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-2693(84)90688-9 F. Dydak et al.: A search for {{SubatomicParticle|muon neutrino}} oscillations in the \u0394<math>m^2</math> range 0.3\u201390 <math>eV^2</math>] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n  \n* [https://knobloch.web.cern.ch/cdhs/cdhs.html Homepage: The CDHS Neutrino Experiment]\n* [https://inspirehep.net/record/1110121 WA1 on INSPIRE-HEP]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{neutrino detectors}}\n{{SPS experiments}}\n[[Category:CERN experiments|SPS]]\n[[Category:Particle experiments]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:The CDHS (WA1) experimental setup.jpg|thumb|The CDHS (WA1) experimental setup at CERN]]\n\n'''CDHS''' was a neutrino experiment at CERN taking data from 1976 until 1984. The experiment was officially referred to as ''WA1''. CDHS was a collaboration of groups from [[CERN]], [[Technical University Dortmund|Dortmund]], [[Heidelberg University|Heidelberg]], [[Saclay]] and later [[Warsaw]]. The collaboration was led by [[Jack Steinberger]]. The experiment was designed to study [[deep inelastic scattering|deep inelastic]] [[neutrino]] interactions in iron.\n\n== Experimental setup ==\n[[File:Technical sketch of the upgraded CDHS detector.png|thumb|Technical sketch of the upgraded CDHS detector]]\nThe core of the detector consisted of 19 (later 20) magnetized iron modules. In the spacings between these, [[wire chamber #Drift chambers|drift chambers]] for track reconstruction were installed. Additionally, plastic [[scintillator|scintillators]] were inserted into the iron. Each iron module therefore served successively as an interaction target, where the neutrinos hit and produced [[particle shower #hadronic showers|hadron showers]], a calorimeter that measured those hadrons' energy and a spectrometer, determining the momenta of produced [[muon]]s via magnetic deflection.<ref name=annual>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/1479923?ln=en CERN Document Server: Annual Report 1976 (Experimental Physics Division)] Retrieved on 14 August 2018</ref><ref name=detector/>\n\nAt the time of its completion in 1976, the overall detector was 20 m long and weighed approximately 1250 tons.\n\nThe experiment was located in CERN's [[List_of_Super_Proton_Synchrotron_experiments#WA experiments|West Area]], in building 182. The [[neutrinos]] (and antineutrinos) were produced by protons from the [[Super Proton Synchrotron]] (SPS) at energies of around 400 GeV, which were shot onto a [[beryllium]] target.<ref name=annual/>\n\n== History ==\nThe experiment was first proposed in July 1973 by a group led by [[Jack Steinberger]] as a two-piece detector. The front should serve as the [[neutrino]] target and [[particle shower #hadronic showers|hadronic shower]] detector, the following second part should detect the [[muon]] traces.<ref name=proposal>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/604411?ln=en CERN Document Server: Proposal to study high-energy neutrino interactions at the SPS] Retrieved on 13 August 2018</ref> It was planned that the four proposing groups from Saclay, Dortmund, Heidelberg and CERN would contribute with complementary expertise and manpower. For example, Saclay was assigned to be in charge of the [[wire chamber #Drift chambers|drift chambers]], whereas CERN should handle the iron core magnets. It were also these four groups that gave the experiment its name: '''''C'''ERN '''D'''ortmund '''H'''eidelberg '''S'''aclay (CDHS)''.\nApproximately 30 people should form the final experiment group.<ref name=memorandum>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/604399?ln=en CERN Document Server: Memorandum following up the proposal] Retrieved on 13 August 2018</ref> \n\nAfter prolongued discussions with the SPS Committee, that was in charge of approving the proposals and distributing available money, an updated proposal for the new detector was submitted in March 1974. The suggested detector was a modular setup consisting of magnetized [[iron]] modules in combination with [[wire chamber #Drift chambers|drift chambers]] and plastic [[scintillator|scintillators]].<ref name=memo74> [https://cds.cern.ch/record/594735?ln=en CERN Document Server: Memorandum - design and physics of the proposed muon spectrometer] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref> This new proposal was approved by the committee in April 1974. Construction started soon after and was completed in 1976. The experiment's official name was ''WA1'', since it was the first approved experiment at CERN's [[List_of_Super_Proton_Synchrotron_experiments#WA experiments|West Area]].\nThe estimated cost of the detector ranged between 6 and 8 million [[Swiss franc|CHF]].<ref name=proposal/> \n\nIn 1979, an upgrade of the experimental setup was proposed.<ref>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/596902?ln=en CERN Document Server:  Request for approval of WA1 improvement programme] Retrieved on 14 August 2018</ref> The main reason for this upgrade was the comparably low resolution of eight of the 19 detector modules. This situation should be improved by inserting twelve new and better modules, resulting in a slightly longer and significantly more accurate machine. The proposal also included the suggestion for a group from [[Warsaw University]], led by Adam Para, to join the project. \nStarting with the long shutdown of the [[Super Proton Synchrotron]] (SPS) from summer 1980 on, the requested changes were implemented. Eventually, half of the experiment's target calorimeters got replaced and the total number of detector modules was increased from 19 to 20. This led to four times higher spatial resolution of the produced particles as well as 25 % more accurate measurements of the deposited hadronic energy. Additionally, four new drift chambers were installed, improving the reconstruction of [[muon]] tracks.<ref>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/1720097?ln=en CERN Document Server:  New developments at WA1 (CERN Bulletin Issue No. 7/1982)] Retrieved on 14 August 2018</ref><ref name=new>[https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01555493 P. Berge et al.: A measurement of differential cross-sections and nucleon structure functions in charged-current neutrino interactions on iron] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref> Later, a liquid [[hydrogen]] tank was added in front of the detector as a target to measure the [[structure function]] of [[proton]]s.<ref name=abra2>[https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01571954 H. Abramovicz et al.: Measurement of neutrino and antineutrino structure functions in hydrogen and iron] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref>\n\nCDHS took data with neutrinos delivered by the SPS from late 1976 until September 1984.\n\n== Results and discoveries ==\nThe scientific goal of the CDHS experiment was to study high energy neutrino interactions. When the incoming [[neutrino]]s (or antineutrinos) were interacting with the target [[iron]], either charged current ([[neutrino|{{SubatomicParticle|neutrino}}]] + [[iron|Fe]] \u2192 [[muon|{{SubatomicParticle|antimuon}}]] + anything) or [[neutral current]] ({{SubatomicParticle|neutrino}} + Fe \u2192 {{SubatomicParticle|neutrino}} + anything) events could be produced.<ref name=detector>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0029-554X(70)90173-4 M. Holder et al.: A detector for high-energy neutrino interactions] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref> \n\nOne of the main objectives of the experiment was to determine the ratio between the neutral and the charged inclusive neutrino [[Cross section (physics)|cross sections]], from which the [[Weinberg angle]] could be inferred.<ref name=highlights>[https://cds.cern.ch/record/2103282?ln=en CERN Document Server: W. D. Schlatter - Highlights from High Energy Neutrino Experiments at CERN] Retrieved on 14 August 2018</ref> [[Neutral currents]] had previously been discovered by the [[Gargamelle]] experiment, which had also provided first estimates of the Weinberg angle. The results were confirmed and measured with much higher precision by CDHS, allowing to predict the mass of the [[top quark]], before it was discovered at the [[Tevatron]], with approximately \u00b140 GeV precision.<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-2693(77)90783-3 M. Holder et al.: Measurement of the neutral to charged current cross section ratio in neutrino and antineutrino interactions] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref><ref name=highlights/> \n\nOther measurements regarding the [[electroweak interaction]] within the [[standard model]] included the measurement of more than one [[muon]]; i.e. dimuon and trimuon events.<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-2693(77)90685-2 M. Holder et al.: Observation of trimuon events produced in neutrino and antineutrino interactions] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref><ref>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-2693(78)90214-9 T. Hansl et al.: Origin of trimuon events in high-energy neutrino interactions] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref>\n\nResults obtained at CDHS provided experimental validation of the [[standard model]], at a time when this model was still in the testing phase. An important step in this regard was the falsification of the alleged \"high-y anomaly\". The value y characterizes the inelasticity of neutrino collisions, i.e. it measures the amount of energy that an incoming neutrino transfers to the [[hadron]]s during their collision. Experiments at [[Fermilab]] had found the so-called \"high-y anomaly\", which challenged the standard model. However, results from CDHS disproved those findings, strengthening the [[standard model]].<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.39.433 M. Holder et al.: Is There a High-y Anomaly in Antineutrino Interactions?] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref> \n\nCDHS examined the nucleon [[structure function]]s, which enabled scientists to confirm the theory of [[quantum chromodynamics]] (QCD).<ref name=abra>[https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01575772 H. Abramovicz: Tests of QCD and Non-Asymptotically-Free Theories of the Strong Interaction by an Analysis of the Nucleon Structure Functions <math>xF_3, F_2</math>, and {{SubatomicParticle|antiquark}} ] Retrieved on 15 August 2018</ref><ref name=new/> This work included the determination of the QCD [[coupling constant#QCD and asymptotic freedom|coupling constant]] <math> \\alpha_\\text{s}</math>, verification of the [[quark]]'s (s = {{sfrac|1|2}}) and [[gluon]]'s (s = 1) [[spin (physics)|spin]], as well as the falsification of both [[Gauge theory|abelian]] theories of [[strong interaction]]s and theories based on scalar gluons.<ref name=abra2/><ref name=abra/>\nAdditionally, the experiments provided insights into the structure of the [[nucleon]], examining the distribution of [[gluon]]s, [[quark]]s and [[antiquark]]s within it. Results from CDHS were in line with the [[Parton (particle physics)|quark parton model]], that assigned [[quark]]s to be point-like [[Parton (particle physics)|parton]]s.<ref name=highlights/>. In this context, it was also confirmed that the number of [[valence quark]]s in a [[nucleon]] is 3.<ref>[http://ep-news.web.cern.ch/content/interview-philippe-bloch CERN Newsletter of the EP Department: Interview with Philippe Bloch ] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref> Finally, the CDHS results allowed to determine the [[momentum]] distribution of [[strange quark]]s and antiquarks within a [[nucleon]].<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01573422 H. Abramovicz et al.: Experimental Study of Opposite-Sign Dimuons Produced in Neutrino and Antineutrino Interactions ] Retrieved on 17 August 2018</ref> \n\nDuring its last years of operation, the CDHS collaboration engaged in the search for [[neutrino oscillation]]s. Although this phenomenon could not be confirmed using CERN's large energy neutrino beam, this attempt influenced the following experiments that eventually discovered [[neutrino oscillation]]s.<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-2693(84)90688-9 F. Dydak et al.: A search for {{SubatomicParticle|muon neutrino}} oscillations in the \u0394<math>m^2</math> range 0.3\u201390 <math>eV^2</math>] Retrieved on 16 August 2018</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://knobloch.home.cern.ch/knobloch/cdhs/cdhs.html Homepage: The CDHS Neutrino Experiment]\n* [https://inspirehep.net/record/1110121 WA1 on INSPIRE-HEP]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{neutrino detectors}}\n{{SPS experiments}}\n[[Category:CERN experiments|SPS]]\n[[Category:Particle experiments]]\n", "name_user": "Gahs", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correct URL for \"Homepage: CDHS Neutrino Experiment \"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CDHS_experiment"}
{"title_page": "Lawrence E. Golub", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Lawrence E. Golub\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place        = \n| baptised           = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| disappeared_date   = <!-- {{disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| burial_place       = <!-- may be used instead of resting_place and resting_place_coordinates - displays \"Burial place\" as label -->\n| burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names        = \n| ethnicity          = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| citizenship        = \n| education          = [[JD/MBA|JD-MBA]]<br>[[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Harvard Law School]]<br>[[Harvard Business School]]<br>[[Harvard College]]\n| occupation         = [[entrepreneur]]<br/>[[philanthropist]]<br/>[[business executive]]\n| years_active       = \n| era                = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| agent              = <!-- Discouraged in most cases, specifically when promotional, and requiring a reliable source -->\n| known_for          = CEO, Golub Capital\n| notable_works      = <!-- produces label \"Notable work\"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label \"Notable credit(s)\"; or by |works=, which produces label \"Works\" -->\n| style              = \n| home_town          = \n| salary             = \n| net_worth          = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height             = <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| weight             = <!-- \"X kg\", \"X lb\" or \"X st Y lb\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| television         = \n| title              = [[Golub Capital]], <small>([[CEO]])</small>\n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| religion           = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination       = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| criminal_charge    = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             = [[Karen Finerman]]\n| partner            = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| callsign           = \n| awards             = \n| website            = [https://www.linkedin.com/in/lawrenceegolub Lawrence Golub - LinkedIn]\n| module             = \n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| signature_alt      = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Lawrence E. Golub''' is an [[United States|American]] entrepreneur, philanthropist, and business executive. He is the CEO of [[Golub Capital]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawrence Golub, Eugene Ludwig on Where the Financing Is|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/lawrence-golub-eugene-ludwig-on-where-the-financing-is-1444096898|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=5 October 2015}}</ref> a credit asset management company he founded in 1994. Prior to Golub Capital, he had management careers with [[Bankers Trust|Bankers Trust Company]] and [[Allen & Company]]. Golub sits on the board of numerous organizations, including the Harvard University JD-MBA Alumni Association and one of three private members of the [[New York State Department of Financial Services|Financial Control Board of the State of New York]].<ref name=CapitalNewYork>{{cite news|last1=Goldenberg|first1=Sally|title=De Blasio gets high marks for city\u2019s fiscal plan|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/city-hall/2014/07/8549894/de-blasio-gets-high-marks-citys-fiscal-plan|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=Capital New York|date=29 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nGolub is a supporter of philanthropic efforts, most notably organizations for medical research for [[Parkinson's disease]].<ref name=WSJparkinsons>{{cite news|last1=West|first1=Melanie Grayce|title=Couple Aids Parkinson's Research|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304070104576399932925940832|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=22 June 2011}}</ref> In 2001, he established the Golub Stem Cell Initiative for Parkinson's with a $500,000 donation to the New York Stem Cell Foundation.<ref name=WSJparkinsons/>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nGolub grew up in New York, his parents both from poor immigrant families.<ref name=ABFJournal>{{cite news|last1=Papavassiliou|first1=Stuart P.|title=Golub Capital - Unique in Every Aspect|url=http://www.abfjournal.com/articles/golub-capital-unique-in-every/|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=ABF Journal|date=October 2010}}</ref> He attended [[Harvard College]] where he received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree ''magna cum laude''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Harvard Stories - Lawrence Golub (video)|url=http://stories.harvard.edu/videos/237|website=Harvard University|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> Golub had an interest in science since high school, studying the emerging DNA technology of the time. He took pre-med classes in college but decided to switch to a major in business.<ref name=WSJparkinsons/> Golub went on to attend [[Harvard Law School]] and [[Harvard Business School]], earning both a JD and an MBA through the school's joint degree program. Golub also founded the Harvard University JD-MBA Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wee|first1=Gillian|title=Fixing Harvard Endowment Failures Will Take Mendilo Five Years|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-09-28/failures-of-harvard-endowment-will-take-five-years-to-fix-in-mendillo-plan|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=Bloomberg Business|date=27 September 2010}}</ref><ref name=NYTRomney>{{cite news|last1=Lattman|first1=Peter|title=Romney, at Harvard, Merged Two Worlds|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/10/us/romney-merged-law-and-business-at-harvard.html?_r=0|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=The New York Times|date=9 July 2012}}</ref> He was selected as a [[Baker Scholar]] at Harvard Business School and was an editor at the [[Harvard Law Review]].<ref name=MotlefFoolBlanceS>{{cite news|last1=Wroblewska|first1=Anna|title=How Golub Capital BDC Inc Built a Hurricane-Proof Balance Sheet|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/07/07/how-golub-capital-bdc-built-a-hurricane-proof-bala.aspx|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=The Motley Fool|date=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nDuring his early career, Golub spent his time working for various well-known banks.<ref name=EconomistUS>{{cite news|title=Pockets of credit; Middle-market banking|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-272664033.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409122802/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-272664033.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 April 2016|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=The Economist|date=19 November 2011}}</ref> He started his career at [[Allen & Company]] where he engaged in private equity, leveraged finance, and mergers and acquisitions.<ref name=ABFJournal/> He went on to become a Managing Director at [[Wasserstein Perella & Co.|Wasserstein Perella]] where he established the firm's capital markets group and debt restructuring practice.<ref name=ABFJournal/> Golub was a White House Fellow and served for fifteen years as Treasurer of the [[White House Fellows|White House Fellows Foundation]].<ref name=MotlefFoolBlanceS/> Prior to starting Golub Capital, he worked as a Managing Director of [[Bankers Trust Company]].<ref name=ABFJournal/>\n\nGolub founded the U.S.-focused credit asset management company Golub Capital in 1994.<ref name=ABFJournal/> The firm has primary business lines in middle market lending, late stage lending, and broadly syndicated loans.<ref name=MFoolGolubBD>{{cite news|last1=Wroblewska|first1=Anna|title=The Secret to Golub Capital BDC Inc's Success|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/06/26/the-secret-to-golub-capitals-success.aspx|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=The Motley Fool|date=26 June 2014}}</ref> The firm is also affiliated with Golub Capital BDC, Inc., a business development company that trades on the NASDAQ under the stock ticker symbol, GBDC. Golub Capital is one of the largest non-bank middle market lenders and providers of senior debt.<ref name=MFoolGolubBD/> In 2016, the firm was named \"Lender of the Year\" by Private Debt Investor.<ref name=MFoolGolubBD/>\n\nGolub serves on the board of numerous organizations, including as President of the Harvard University JD-MBA Alumni Association. He is one of three private members of the Financial Control Board of the State of New York.<ref name=CapitalNewYork/> He is also a member of the Harvard University Committee on University Resources.<ref name=IDDigest>{{cite news|title=Investing In a Cure: The Golub Family Donates Generously to Fight Parkinson's Disease|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-163042121.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120153203/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-163042121.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 November 2018|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=Investment Dealer's Digest|date=7 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nGolub is married to American businesswoman and television personality [[Karen Finerman]], president and chief executive of New York-based hedge fund Metropolitan Capital Advisors.<ref name=ABFJournal/> They are the parents of two sets of twins.<ref name=ABFJournal/>\n\nGolub is active in charitable and civic organizations. Golub and his family actively support medical research to advance treatments for Parkinson's disease at several leading institutions.<ref name=WSJparkinsons/> In 2001, he established the Golub Stem Cell Initiative for Parkinson's with a $500,000 donation to the New York Stem Cell Foundation.<ref name=WSJparkinsons/> He also funded a Parkinson's research effort within the Harvard Stem Cell Institute, which currently focuses on Parkinson's, juvenile diabetes, and ALS.<ref name=IDDigest/>\n\nGolub was Chairman of Mosholu Preservation Corporation, a non-profit developer and manager of low-income housing in the Bronx.<ref>{{cite news|title=Financing Public-To-Private Companies: Lawrence Golub - Golub Associates Inc.|url=https://www.twst.com/interview/financing-public-to-private-companies-lawrence-golub-golub-associates-inc|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=The Wall Street Transcript|date=4 March 2004}}</ref> He served for fifteen years as a trustee of Montefiore Medical Center, the university hospital of the Albert Einstein Medical School.<ref>{{cite web|title=Strategic M&A Deals - Regions, Sectors and Structures|url=http://www.thedeal.com/knowledge/merrill-datasite/strategic-ma-deals---regions-sectors-and-structures.php|website=The Deal|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He also served for six years as a trustee of Horace Mann School and for five years on the Harvard University Committee for Science and Engineering.<ref name=IDDigest/><ref>{{cite web|title=Outstanding Investor Speaker Series Features Lawrence Golub, HBS '83|url=http://www.hbscny.org/article.html?aid=1086|website=Harvard Business School Club of New York|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{LinkedIn URL|https://www.linkedin.com/in/lawrenceegolub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golub, Lawrence E.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Lawrence E. Golub\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place        = \n| baptised           = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| disappeared_date   = <!-- {{disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {